Averting a showdown, centrists from both parties reached agreement on a compromise that clears the way for confirmation votes on many of President George W. Bush's stalled judicial nominees, leaves others in limbo and preserves Senate filibuster rules.
"In a Senate that is increasingly polarized, the bipartisan center held," Democratic Sen Joseph Lieberman said Monday night.
The two page memorandum of agreement said it is "based upon mutual trust and confidence."
Under the terms, Democrats would agree to oppose any attempt to filibuster and thus block final votes on the confirmation of Priscilla Owen, Janice Rogers Brown and William Pryor.
There is "no commitment to vote for or against" the filibuster against two other conservative nominees, Henry Saad and William Myers.
Despite behind the scenes efforts at compromise, partisan lines deepened in the Senate's historic debate over judicial nominees Thursday as a Republican who had advocated finding a middle ground lined up behind the GOP's leadership and both parties injected racial politics into the fight.
Another sign of the hardening of positions came late in the afternoon Thursday when Sen Rick Santorum, R Pa., chairman of the Republican Conference, the No. 3 job in the leadership, invoked Adolph Hitler in his criticism of Democrats.
Santorum said Democrats broke Senate rules with their filibusters of judicial nominees two years ago.
Their criticism now of Republican efforts to change the rules on debating judicial nominees is "the equivalent of Adolph Hitler in 1942 saying, 'I'm in Paris.
How dare you invade me.
How dare you bomb my city?
It's mine."'
There was no immediate response from the Democratic leadership, but the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee (DSCC) posted a video of Santorum's remarks on the Internet shortly after he left the Senate floor.
Sen Gordon Smith, R Ore., once a self described "qualified supporter" of Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist's efforts to force a vote on the judges, announced in the second day of heated debate that his is now an "unqualified" backer of Frist.
Still, a handful of moderates in both parties continued their talks to find a compromise short of the so called "nuclear option" under consideration by Frist a parliamentary maneuver that would make it easier to confirm federal judges but also profoundly alter the way the Senate conducts its affairs.
Those talks took place in the privacy of Senate offices in contrast to the public debate on the Senate floor that seemed to become more heated by the hour, each side accusing the other of political motives well beyond the sole judicial nominee under consideration, Priscilla Owen of Texas.
But both parties used another pending nomination, that of Janice Rogers Brown of California, an African American native of Alabama, to reach out to blacks in the fight over Senate procedures in addressing judicial nominations.
Sen Johnny Isakson, R Ga., recalled the infamous filibusters of Southern segregationists in the 1960s who tried to block passage of major civil rights legislation.
"I would hope that today the filibuster would not be used to deny an up or down vote on Janice Rogers Brown, because every parent deserves to dream for every child that they'll have a chance ,," he said.
Isakson's comments on the Senate floor coincided with Frist's appearance at a news conference outside the Capitol with a group of black ministers, including Bishop Wellington Boone of The Father's House in Atlanta, in support of Brown's nomination to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
Although Frist did not mention Brown's race, the Senate majority leader said the Democratic treatment of her nomination was "uncivil" and he vowed that he will "do everything in my power to see that it stops."
At a separate news conference in the Hart Senate office building, Rev. Timothy McDonald, chairman of the African American Ministers in Action (AAMIA), disputed suggestions that racism and sexism are behind opposition to Brown and Owen.
"Believe me, we know well that there are too few African Americans and too few women on the courts," said McDonald, pastor of the First Iconium Baptist Church in Atlanta.
"We would like nothing more than to remedy this problem.
But appointing judges who will use their powerful positions to issue rulings that hurt women and racial minorities will not solve the problem."
Frist's appearance at the news conference followed his refusal to meet with members of the Congressional Black Caucus, a group of House Democrats who told Frist in a letter that a ban on judicial filibusters "would be particularly offensive to people of color."
Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D Nev., showing support for the Congressional Black Caucus, noted that "our nation's judges and courts have often been the last resort for minorities seeking redress from inadequate or unfair laws" but that could change if the Democrats can't block "radical" judges.
Frist said the dispute was really about Senatorial responsibility.
While Democrats are entitled to oppose Owen's nomination to a seat on the New Orleans based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Frist said, "they should not hide behind a procedure that prevents 100 United States senators from their responsibility, their duty to vote 'yes' or 'no' on the nominee."
The Tennessee Republican was referring to the Democrats' use of unlimited debate, or the filibuster, to stall a confirmation vote on 10 of Bush's appellate court nominees in the last Congress.
While only a simple majority of 51 is required to confirm a judge, Senate rules require 60 votes to cut off debate and 67 votes to change the rules.
But Frist is considering a procedure whereby the Senate's presiding officer, Vice President Dick Cheney, will rule that it is unconstitutional to filibuster a federal appeals court nomination, a ruling that could be upheld by at least 51 votes, ending debate and clearing the way for an up or down vote on the nominee.
The issue of how judicial nominations will be addressed in the Senate has taken on a new intensity with the prospect of several Supreme Court nominations in the final three and a half years of Bush's presidency, enough to solidify a conservative majority on the nine member court for a generation.
Smith was the first of several Republican senators to cite Bush's victory in the 2004 presidential election as part of their reason for backing Frist's attempt to remove the filibuster from the Democrats' parliamentary arsenal before there are any battles over Supreme Court nominees.
"Elections have consequences," Smith said.
"The president has rights (to appoint judges of his choice) ,and we have a job to do."
But the Democrat Bush defeated in the 2004 election, Sen John Kerry of Massachusetts, cautioned that the attempt by the Republican majority to change the Senate's rules in such an unusual way represents "a dangerous time for our democracy."
