An outspoken conservative California judge criticized by Democrats as the most extreme of the president's judicial nominees won confirmation to the nation's most important appellate court Wednesday in a largely party line Senate vote.
In a vote that had been blocked by a Democratic filibuster for the past two years, the Senate approved, 56 43, the appointment of Janice Rogers Brown to the powerful U.S. District Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
Brown became the second of three long stalled judicial nominees who will win Senate votes because of a deal struck by 14 moderate senators to avert a partisan showdown over the Democrats' filibusters of the president's judge nominees.
Late last month, the long delayed nomination of Texas state judge Priscilla Owen to the 5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans was approved in the Senate under the deal.
And the Senate voted Wednesday 67 32 to end debate, and foreclose any more filibustering, on the nomination to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta of former Alabama State's Attorney William Pryor.
A vote on him is expected Thursday or Friday.
Majority Leader Bill Frist, whose bid to strip Democrats of their use of the filibuster on judges was undercut by moderates, praised the confirmation of Brown, saying, "Principle has won a victory over partisan judicial obstruction."
Indeed, Republicans can claim a victory by forcing a vote and confirming three judicial nominees adamantly opposed by Democrats and considered by liberals to be too ideologically conservative.
"They are getting what they want," said Carl Tobias, a law professor at the University of Richmond in Virginia.
"Now the question is what do the Democrats get out of this agreement?"
Democrats have accepted the deal by the seven Republican and seven Democratic moderates because it preserves their right to use a filibuster against judicial nominees, though only in "extraordinary circumstances."
That will matter most if there is a vacancy on the Supreme Court, a possibility widely seen as likely given the serious illness of Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
The Senate opened debate Monday on President Bush's contentious nomination of California State Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown to the federal bench, with Republicans praising her as a "great talent" while Democrats derided her as a conservative ideologue.
The arguments were familiar ones concerning Brown.
First nominated to the federal appeals court for the District of Columbia by Bush in 2003, she was among several presidential choices Democrats blocked through filibuster threats during his first term.
Bush renominated her earlier this year.
Republican Senate leaders wanted to strip Democrats of their right to filibuster judicial nominees until a compromise in late May among centrists in both parties cleared the way for votes on some of the disputed nominees, including Brown.
A vote to end debate on Brown, known as "cloture," is expected Tuesday, and Brown's confirmation vote could come as early as Wednesday.
Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R Tenn., on Monday said Brown, the first black woman to serve on the California Supreme Court, rose to the top of the legal profession through "great achievement and great talent."
Frist noted that she was the daughter of an Alabama sharecropper.
Her father also spent much of his career in the Air Force.
Frist said that, "After being delayed for two years by partisan obstruction (Brown's nomination) will finally get an up or down vote, which she deserves."
Democrats, even as they took note of the agreement to end the filibuster of Brown, urged senators to vote against her confirmation, based on her legal record.
Sen Barbara Boxer, D Calif., criticized Brown for taking an extremely limited view of government regulation in opinions that argued for rolling back the Social Security programs or zoning ordinances.
"It's not her life that I attack when I say I'm not for Janice Rogers Brown.
It's what she will do to your life," Boxer said, referring to the public.
She added, "Packing the courts with people like this will set our country back."
Brown's nomination is opposed by most black members of Congress, all of whom are Democrats.
"Both in her court decisions and in her many writings, Ms Brown rejects the civil rights remedies Congress has enacted and that the courts have approved ,and believes that parts of ,the 1964 Civil Rights Act are unconstitutional," Rep Melvin L. Watt, D N.C., chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus, said in a statement.
At a news conference, Democratic leader Harry Reid, D Nev., accused Bush of entangling Congress in a conflict over judicial nominations by sending the Senate controversial nominees like Brown instead of consensus candidates.
"This whole legislative year, we have yet to spend a single minute debating health care, debating education, debating the environment, debating the things that people in America feel important," Reid said.
"That's too bad.
These radical judges don't deserve the attention that these other issues do."
Republicans have responded to such criticism by accusing Democrats of unfairly using the filibuster to thwart Bush and a GOP controlled Senate from filling vacancies on the federal bench.
The controversy over confirming federal judges appears to have taken a toll on the public's approval of Congress.
In a Gallup poll released Monday, just 22 percent of respondents said they have "a great deal" or "quite a lot" of confidence in Congress the lowest rating since 1997 and down from 30 percent last year.
Fifty one percent of respondents said they have "some" confidence, and 26 percent said they have "very little" or "none."
Gallup said Congress ranks with big business and organized labor among 15 institutions tested, and only slightly better than the lowest rated institution, health maintenance organizations.
The poll of 1000 adults had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
Republicans filed a motion Friday to end debate on the nomination of Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen to the federal bench, a move starting the countdown to the so called nuclear option.
The motion schedules for Tuesday the long anticipated showdown over whether Democrats have the right to use the parliamentary tactic known as the filibuster to block President Bush's judicial nominations.
Before filing the motion, Sen John Cornyn, R Texas, accused Democrats of exaggerating when they call the dispute a "constitutional crisis."
"This is a controversy, but not a crisis," Cornyn said.
"And I hope that in the coming days, we will complete our debate and resolve the controversy in a respectful manner, consistent with the greatest traditions of the United States Senate."
But the Republican push to ban the filibuster for judicial nominees has become known as the nuclear option because of the partisan discord it would spark in the Senate.
Democrats, for instance, have threatened to stall much of the chamber's business if the ban is adopted.
A group of a dozen senators still held out hope Friday of averting the showdown by refusing to lend their votes to either side.
Six Republicans and six Democrats are discussing a draft agreement under which Democrats would pledge not to use the filibuster in the future, except under "extraordinary circumstances."
In return, Republicans would pledge not to lend their votes to the effort to change the filibuster rules, unless at some point they think the Democrats had violated the spirit of the agreement.
In addition, five of seven Bush nominees to the federal appellate courts would be given confirmation votes.
And the senators would call on the White House to consult with the chamber in advance of submitting nominations, especially those to the Supreme Court.
Sen Robert C. Byrd, D W.Va., has revived a proposal to have the Senate Judiciary Committee, perhaps with the advice of an independent commission, provide the president with a list of potential nominees who would have bipartisan support.
Sen Lamar Alexander, R Tenn., said Friday that perhaps 80 percent of senators, while unwilling to buck party leaders by signing onto the compromise, nonetheless hoped it succeeds.
"This oncoming train wreck is bad for the Senate, it is bad for the country, it is bad for the Democrats and it is bad for the Republicans," he said on the Senate floor.
"We look pretty silly lecturing Iraq on how to set up a government when we can't even decide on having an up or down vote on President Bush's judicial nominees."
Senate Republican and Democratic leaders have said they would accept no deal that violates their fundamental principles: for Republicans, that all judicial nominees be allowed confirmation votes that are decided by a simple majority, for Democrats, that no changes be made in the rules governing the filibuster.
The filibuster is the right of senators to engage in extended debate on an issue.
It takes 60 votes to end debate in the 100 seat chamber.
The debate on Owen's nomination to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans began Wednesday.
Democrats are attempting to thwart a confirmation vote of her because they view her as an "extremist" conservative.
Democrats have used the filibuster threat to block 10 of Bush's appellate court nominees during his first term.
Bush renominated seven of them, including Owen and California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown.
Republicans say using the filibusters on so many nominees is unprecedented and breaks 200 years of tradition.
Democrats say the president's decision to renominate so many judges unacceptable to them is unprecedented.
They also say GOP plans to change the filibuster rules will rend Senate traditions that protect the rights of the minority party.
Since there are 44 Democrats and an independent who usually sides with them in the Senate, Republicans are expected to lose Tuesday's vote to end debate on Owen's nomination.
At that point, party leaders say they will conduct a series of maneuvers to establish a new procedure for confirming judges.
Vice President Dick Cheney is expected to preside over the session in his capacity as president of the Senate, in case his vote is needed to break a tie.
(Optional add end) First, Majority Leader Bill Frist, R Tenn., would ask Cheney for a ruling on whether senators should have a right to vote on whether to proceed to a confirmation vote.
Cheney is expected to rule in favor of Frist, and Democratic leader Harry Reid, D Nev., is expected to object.
Senators would then vote on whether to table, or reject, the Democratic objection.
Since Republicans are in the majority, the objection would likely be rejected.
At that point, Frist would ask senators to vote on whether to proceed to a final confirmation vote, which would likely pass, and then he would ask senators to vote on Owen's confirmation.
Both votes would require a simple majority of 51.
The result of Cheney's ruling, followed by the three votes, would be to establish a new parliamentary procedure for considering judicial nominations that would bypass a cloture vote to end debate, thereby making the filibuster useless as a stalling static.
In contrast to the previous days, debate on the Senate floor had a desultory air Friday, as senators saved their remaining ammunition for the coming week.
Senate aides said that debate on Monday would begin in the afternoon and could last deep into the night.
Meanwhile, Sen Rick Santorum, R Pa., issued an apology for remarks on the Senate floor the previous day in which he invoked the name of Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler in criticizing Democrats.
"Referencing Hitler was meant to dramatize the principle of an argument, not to characterize my Democratic colleagues," Santorum said, in a statement.
"It was a mistake and I meant no offense."
The Senate voted 56 43 to elevate conservative California jurist Janice Rogers Brown to the nation's most important federal appeals court Wednesday, the second of President Bush's controversial nominees to win confirmation under a special agreement between centrist Republicans and Democrats.
Brown, 55, a member of the California Supreme Court, won confirmation after nearly two years of efforts by Democrats to deny her a lifetime appointment to the federal bench, contending that she has ignored legal precedents with rulings that promote an ultra conservative political agenda.
But her Republican supporters have countered that she is a model of judicial restraint, and in nearly every speech from the Senate floor in recent weeks, they have lauded her rise from a poor childhood in segregated Alabama to prominence as a judge.
But while many white Republican senators praised Brown as a role model for African Americans, the only African American in the Senate, Barak Obama, D Ill., voted against her and cautioned that Brown was not deserving of support "just because she is a black woman."
Before the vote, members of the Congressional Black Caucus walked into the Senate to demonstrate their opposition to Brown.
"Send a message that extremists are unacceptable to the federal judiciary," Rep Melvin Watt, D N.C., said in a statement.
The Senate vote clears the way for Brown to take a seat on the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, one of 12 courts of appeal in the federal judiciary, but the only one with special jurisdiction over legal challenges arising from decisions and rules of federal agencies located in Washington.
The Senate also voted 67 32 to end debate on Bush's nomination of former Alabama attorney general William Pryor to a permanent seat on the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based in Atlanta.
Pryor has been serving on the court under a temporary appointment since February 2004.
By ending debate on Pryor's nomination, the Senate set the stage for his confirmation as well, probably Thursday, the last confirmation vote guaranteed under an agreement reached by the "Gang of 14" senators from both parties to avoid a potentially damaging fight over the Senate's rules on debate.
The agreement, while granting a floor vote to long stalled Bush judicial nominees Brown, Pryor and Priscilla Owen, confirmed to a seat on the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, also preserved the right of the Democratic minority to filibuster future nominees under undefined "extraordinary conditions."
Whether such conditions will be present after Pryor's floor vote is unclear, but Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R Tenn., has reiterated he will undertake special and controversial procedures to prevent any further filibusters of judicial nominees by the Democrats.
But immediately after Wednesday's votes, Frist said the Senate had "broken the impasse" on judicial nominees and, after confirmation votes on Pryor and a handful of non controversial pending nominations, the Senate will begin work on energy legislation, probably next week.
"The American people will know we're doing the nation's business," added Frist.
Congressional approval ratings have plummeted this spring, and Democrats have charged that the Republican controlled Senate has spent too much time on Bush's judicial nominees instead of dealing with the country's problems.
"We've spent endless hours, endless days, too many weeks debating radical judges and Republican attempts to abuse power," Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D Nev., said.
Four polls conducted last month found Congress with its lowest levels of public support in more than a decade.
The fight over the nominees has not only dominated the work of the Senate but has deepened the political divide in the nation's capital because of the potential the president has to reshape the federal government in his conservative image through such lifetime appointments.
And the Senate vote confirming Brown produced a flood of responses from interest groups reflecting that political divide.
"It is a sad day for the Senate and for Americans who are counting on senators to fulfill their constitutional duty to evaluate every judicial nominee carefully and confirm only those who will uphold Americans' constitutional rights and legal protections," said Ralph Neas, president of People For The American Way, the group most active in opposing her nomination.
"The Senate has set a standard for fairness with Janice Rogers Brown and we expect the same for the remaining judicial nominees," said Tony Perkins, president of Family Research Council, a Washington organization that has rallied evangelical Christians to the cause of confirming Bush's nominees.
Both sides are especially interested in the possibility of a Supreme Court vacancy this summer.
Chief Justice William Rehnquist is 80 years old and suffering from cancer.
