Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist on Tuesday moved the chamber closer to a long threatened showdown between Republicans and Democrats over President Bush's controversial judicial nominations.
Frist, R Tenn., said he intends to bring the first of several of Bush's nominations to the Senate floor for a vote after the chamber passes a transportation funding bill, which is expected by the end of this week.
"Now is the time to address" the judicial issue, Frist said at his weekly news conference.
Democrats are threatening to filibuster three of the four judicial nominees currently awaiting confirmation by the Senate.
As soon as Democrats call a filibuster on one of them, Frist has said he will move to change the rules of the Senate to prohibit use of the procedure to block the confirmation votes.
It takes 60 votes to cut off a filibuster.
During Bush's first term, Democrats used the threat of a filibuster to block votes on 10 of his choices for federal appellate courts, charging the nominees were "extremist" in their conservative views.
Democrats participated in the confirmation of about 200 judicial nominees.
Earlier this year, Bush renominated seven of those who were blocked.
If the rule change on the filibuster passes, it would clear the way for all of the Bush nominees to have up or down votes on their appointments.
To win confirmation, they would need 51 votes in the 100 seat Senate.
Republicans accuse Democrats of breaking Senate tradition by resorting to the filibuster threat to block judges.
Democrats accuse Bush and his Republican allies of breaking tradition by continuing to push for controversial choices.
Frist declined to say which nominee he expected to bring up first for a vote a choice that would determine how rapidly the confrontation escalates.
Earlier this week, Sen Harry Reid, the minority leader from Nevada, urged Frist to defuse tensions by proceeding with one of the less controversial nominees.
He suggested starting with Thomas Griffith, who Bush has picked to serve on the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
Griffith is one of the four nominees pending before the Senate.
Reid said that although many Democrats oppose still him, they would not organize a filibuster against him.
On Thursday, the Senate Judiciary Committee is expected to send a fifth nominee to the Senate floor William H. Pryor Jr., who was renominated by Bush to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
Although Democrats filibustered his nomination in the past, they have signaled that they will not do so again.
"We don't like any of those five," Reid said.
"But in an effort to work toward saving this institution ,I would be willing to give up on any one of those five."
But that left open the prospect that Democrats would filibuster Bush's other controversial nominees.
The other nominees pending before the full Senate are California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown, Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen a favorite among conservative activists and William Myers, a former ranching and mining lobbyist.
Republican leaders have sent conflicting signals about which of the nominees they would likely bring to the floor first.
In his comments to reporters, Frist singled out Owen for praise, saying that "it is just wrong that we do not allow her, after four years (since she was first nominated), that courtesy of an up or down vote."
But a short while later, former California Gov. Pete Wilson appeared at the Republicans' weekly policy luncheon to brief his former Senate colleagues about Brown, who served for three years as his legal affairs advisor.
Afterward, Wilson said he believes Democrats are trying to "demonize" her, comparing her nomination to that of Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas.
Brown and Thomas are both black.
"I think that is most anathema to her Democratic critics they don't like the idea of articulate conservatives and they particularly don't like when it's a person of color," Wilson said.
"I don't think that's a new phenomenon here."
Both sides acknowledge that the central issue is less the current list of nominees than the looming possibility of a Supreme Court vacancy later this year.
"This fight is not about the seven radical nominations," Reid told reporters.
"It's about clearing the way for a Supreme Court nominee who only needs 51 votes, not 60," for confirmation.
Frist said that Republicans "have to look to the future to see that nominees for ,the circuit court level and the Supreme Court have that opportunity for an up or down vote."
Leaders on both sides said Tuesday they saw little room for a deal to avert the confrontation.
A divided Senate Judiciary Committee on Thursday sent two controversial appeals court nominees toward a showdown vote in the Senate, setting the stage for what Democrats described as a looming "constitutional crisis" over President Bush's judicial nominations.
With Democrats forming a solid wall of dissent, the Republican dominated committee voted 10 8 to revive the long dormant nominations of Priscilla Owen of Texas and Janice Rogers Brown of California.
The two were blocked by threatened Democratic filibusters during the last session of Congress.
The action propels the Senate toward a volatile, partisan confrontation, with Republicans contemplating a rules change that would prohibit further judicial filibusters and enable Bush to win Senate confirmation of his embattled court appointees.
Democrats describe the rules change as a "nuclear option" and are threatening to slow down Senate business if Republicans persist.
"This is an important and historic meeting," declared Sen Charles Schumer, D N.Y. "We're in the ramp up to a great constitutional crisis."
Republicans, who have a majority in the 100 member Senate, say the time has come to end what they describe as politically motivated obstructionist tactics by Democrats and sustain the president's right to send his nominees to the bench.
Democrats, in turn, say they have helped confirm 205 judicial nominees but object to a handful who are either unqualified or too extreme to hold life time judicial appointments.
Owen, a Texas Supreme Court justice nominated to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans, has been held up for nearly four years amid Democratic allegations that she injected anti abortion sentiments into her opinions and consistently handed down rulings that penalized consumers and favored big business.
Her supporters dismiss those characterizations as groundless, describing the former Houston attorney as fair minded and more than qualified.
The American Bar Association gave Owen its highest recommendation in examining her qualifications for nomination.
"She deserves to be confirmed," said Sen John Cornyn, R Texas, a member of the committee.
"She's waited four years for an up and down vote in the United States Senate."
"The way she's been treated is less than humane," said Sen Orrin Hatch, R Utah.
But leading Democrats stood firm in their opposition to Owen.
"Nothing has changed since we last reviewed her record to make Justice Owen worthy of confirmation now," said Sen Edward M. Kennedy, D Mass. "If anything, her decisions since then only confirm that she should not receive a life time position on the 5th Circuit."
Schumer said he was "proud to oppose this nomination."
Brown, who now serves on the California Supreme Court, was nominated to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in the District of Columbia, which deals with cases involving much of the federal government and is often described as second only to the Supreme Court in importance.
Democrats said that she would use the bench to advance "extremist" conservative views, but Sen Jeff Sessions, R Ala., countered that the jurist is independent and hard working, "with an open mind" and "a lot of common sense."
Senate rules require 60 votes to stop a filibuster, traditionally long winded speeches designed to block or delay Senate action.
The rules change being considered by Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R Tenn., would allow a simple 51 vote majority to end a filibuster.
Republicans have 55 votes, compared to 44 for Democrats and one for the lone independent senator, Jim Jeffords of Vermont.
