WASHINGTON Moderate Democratic and Republican senators met into the evening Tuesday night in the hopes of avoiding a showdown over filibusters of judicial nominees, as Republican leaders planned to launch a carefully choreographed debate on the issue of judges Wednesday that they hope will bring public opinion to their side.
About a dozen senators met behind closed doors with Senate majority leader Bill Frist and Senate minority leader Harry Reid for about an hour late Tuesday afternoon to discuss the framework of the proposed compromise.
However, a senior Democratic aide said Tuesday night that the two leaders left the meeting as far apart as ever, though that does not foreclose the possibility of rank and file members reaching an agreement on their own.
Senator Ben Nelson, a Nebraska Democrat who is among the leaders of the group seeking a compromise, emerged from the meeting saying they were drawing close to a deal but remained short of persuading the six Democrats and six Republicans they need to seal the deal.
The agreement under discussion would bind the Republicans to preserving Democrats' right to filibuster judges, on the condition that Democrats only use filibusters in "extreme circumstances," Nelson said.
Still undecided, however, is the fate of eight men and women the White House has already nominated for judgeships and Democratic leaders have promised to filibuster.
Under the deal, "There'll be judicious use of the filibuster, and you won't have a nuclear option a banning of filibusters in this session of Congress," Nelson told reporters after the meeting.
It remained unclear Tuesday whether Frist would sign off on such a deal, however.
The Tennessee Republican refused to comment on his way out of the meeting, but has said he will not take any deal that doesn't guarantee votes for all nominees on the Senate floor.
In addition, Frist is under pressure from conservatives to ban filibusters before a vacancy arises on the Supreme Court, and the proposed agreement would not accomplish that.
As of Tuesday night, Frist remained on track to force the issue on the Senate floor, starting Wednesday morning.
Frist is moving to confirm two female judges with compelling life stories, making it more difficult for Democrats to stand against them.
Republicans plan to stretch debate over several days and make a show of trying to cut the Democrats off through normal procedures, a move intended to highlight the perception of Democratic obstructionism, Republican senators said.
"When you want to score, you run your best plays," said Senator George Allen, Republican of Virginia.
"And if it's tough for the Democrats, that's fine with me."
Frist will bring up the nominations of Priscilla Owen and Janice Rogers Brown Wednesday through the Senate's regular operating rules, but a vote is unlikely to happen before next Tuesday or Wednesday, according to Frist's top aides.
Frist hosted Owen and Rogers Brown for a photo opportunity Tuesday at his office shortly after the two met with President Bush at the White House.
"Our simple goal is to restore that 214 years of tradition to allow these nominees a simple, fair up or down vote," Frist said at a news conference.
Democrats are fighting back by citing inflammatory statements and decisions handed down by Owen and Rogers Brown.
They are planning a series of public events to state opposition to the judges, and to any rules change that would make their confirmations possible.
Under Senate rules, as few as 41 senators can force unlimited debate through a procedure known as a filibuster, effectively killing a nomination.
Democrats used that power to scuttle 10 of Bush's 218 judicial nominees in his first term, and have vowed to do the same to defeat at least the seven he has re nominated this year.
Frist has promised to use a parliamentary maneuver that would outlaw those filibusters, in essence lowering the threshold for confirmation from 60 votes to 50 votes.
Conservatives are anxious for the rules to be changed before a Supreme Court vacancy, but Democrats have vowed to slow Senate business to a crawl in response.
The proposed compromise being spearheaded by Nelson and Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona would probably be acceptable to Reid if it preserves Democrats' ability to filibuster judges in the future, according to aides to the Democratic leader.
If the future of filibusters comes to a vote in the Senate, neither side is sure of the outcome.
Frist's maneuver needs 50 votes to succeed, and while Republicans control 55 Senate seats, two senators have announced plans to side with the Democrats and at least half a dozen others are publicly undecided.
