Moderate Democrats and Republicans failed Tuesday to derail a confrontation over federal judgeships that both sides said would begin playing out Wednesday on the floor of the Senate.
Republican leaders said they would start the day's Senate session by fopening debate on President Bush's nomination of Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen to the federal appeals court in New Orleans.
The nomination of California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown to the federal appeals court in the District of Columbia also will be discussed in the coming days, but Republicans have decided to focus on Owen in their dispute with Democrats over judicial nominees.
Democrats previously used filibusters to block the nominations of Owen and Brown and have said they would seek to do so again, setting the stage for the Senate showdown.
Bush turned up the heat on the issue, saying Tuesday night that senators have "a duty to promptly consider each of these nominees on the Senate floor, discuss and debate their qualifications, and then give them the up or down vote they deserve" rather than filibuster them.
Bush's remarks to 1500 donors attending a Republican Party fund raising gala represented an escalation of the administration's campaign to pressure the Senate to act.
In the hours before the parliamentary battle was to begin, the spotlight shone on a dozen or so centrists from both parties who discussed a potential compromise to defuse the dispute.
After an hour and a half of discussions Tuesday evening that included Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R Tenn., and Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D Nev., the meeting broke up with no progress reported.
The lead Democrat in the effort, Sen Ben Nelson of Nebraska, told reporters that talks would continue.
"Every time you talk, you gain ground, you don't lose ground," Nelson said.
The confrontation has been building for years as each party has used various methods to thwart the other party's nominations to the federal courts.
In recent years, Democrats used the filibuster in which a senator's right to extended debate is used as a stalling tactic to block votes on 10 of Bush's nominations to federal appellate courts.
Democrats argued that those judges were conservative ideologues.
Currently, 60 votes are needed to end a filibuster and force a confirmation vote, Republicans want to lower the threshold to 51 votes for judicial nominees.
"I really think people on both sides don't want this to happen," said Sen Joe Lieberman, D Conn., one of those working for a compromise.
"Members on both sides don't want the explosion to occur."
The proposed compromise, brokered by Nelson and Sen John McCain, R Ariz., would be a pact between six Republicans and six Democrats to vote together to end filibusters of the stalled judicial nominees but also oppose any change in the rules permitting such filibusters.
Republicans hold 55 seats in the 100 member Senate, so six GOP defectors would be enough to deny Frist a majority vote on the filibuster issue.
Owen and Brown, the two judges at the heart of the Republican campaign against the filibuster, were in Washington Tuesday.
They had lunch at the White House with Bush's chief counsel, Harriet Miers, dropped by the Oval Office for a brief visit with Bush and then made a carefully orchestrated appearance on Capitol Hill.
The confrontation is expected to play out over the coming week in stages and culminate early next week.
Owen is a favorite of abortion opponents and religious conservatives because of several legal opinions she wrote denying minors the right to an abortion without parental notification.
Brown, who is black, is considered more likely to attract the support of independents and Republican moderates.
A senior Frist aide said Tuesday that Brown's nomination will move to the Senate floor after confirmation votes for Owen and John R. Bolton, Bush's nominee for U.N. ambassador.
As a result, Brown's confirmation battle is unlikely to reach the Senate floor until after Memorial Day.
The aide spoke on condition of anonymity because the scenario was preliminary.
The second stage is expected to begin Friday, the aide said, when Republicans will file a motion to end debate on Owen.
Two days later, the Senate will hold a vote on the motion, known as "cloture," which requires 60 votes.
Republicans are expected to lose that vote, at which point Frist will begin the climactic chapter, according to his aide.
With Vice President Dick Cheney presiding over the chamber in his capacity as president of the Senate, Frist will make a motion suggesting that senators should have the right to vote on judicial nominees after a certain number of hours of debate have passed.
Cheney is expected to uphold the motion, Democrats are expected to object, and the chamber will vote on whether to table, or reject, the Democratic appeal.
All those votes require a simple majority, the aide said, and Cheney could break a possible tie.
Frist's motion would establish a precedent, he said, under which all judicial nominations would get a vote after a certain amount of debate and confirmation would require 51 votes.
The precedent would apply to all federal judges, including the Supreme Court.
