Commissioner Bud Selig and Major League Baseball have taken a lot of heat over the last several months for their supposed failure to grapple forthrightly with the sport's steroid problem.
Some have even suggested that people in the commissioner's office have been winking at one another while they make public pronouncements against steroid use.
From my perspective, these critics are jumping to unfair conclusions.
They would benefit from taking a step back and looking more carefully at the evolution of the steroid problem in baseball.
Before the mid 1990s, the substances of choice in the clubhouse were amphetamines and recreational drugs.
The prevailing view was that top offensive performances in baseball demanded quick reflexes, good eye hand coordination, quick feet, flexibility and strong wrists not bulky muscles.
An FBI special agent, Greg Stejskal, told the news media last month that he had notified Major League Baseball about 10 years ago that steroid use was a developing problem.
Indeed, it was probably around 10 years ago that some people in baseball became aware that anabolic steroids were being used by some players.
At the time, many anabolic steroids were illegal if purchased without a prescription.
But as baseball became more aware of this as a growing issue, the commissioner's office did, in fact, act.
In 1998, Selig convened a group at his Milwaukee office, including team physicians, trainers and outside medical experts, and they decided to begin an investigation and to gather as much information about steroid use and its effects as possible.
The next year, together with the players union, baseball helped finance a study on androstenedione.
It turned out to be the seminal study on the substance and was later published in a leading medical journal.
In June 2001, Major League Baseball published a pamphlet in English and in Spanish and distributed it to major league and minor league players.
It laid out in considerable detail the known effects of various classes of performance enhancing drugs.
It also hired a new medical staff to advise it on drug policy.
Baseball reasoned that if it could get players to the majors clean, then it had won half the battle.
In the same year, it decided to put in a stringent testing and penalty program for the minor leagues.
Incidentally, it wasn't until May 2002 that Ken Caminiti, in an interview with Sports Illustrated, estimated that half of major leaguers were using steroids.
In 2002, baseball and the union agreed to their first steroid testing and penalty program.
Earlier this year it was agreed in the middle of a collective bargaining agreement to extend that program significantly.
It would be easy to go back and identify instances when baseball might have gotten the message sooner.
It would be equally easy to argue that baseball might have acted sooner or more punitively.
It is a safe bet that today Selig and others wish they had done more earlier.
Indeed, the new testing and penalty protocol is far from perfect.
But it is also proper to remember that baseball was hampered by the confidentiality of doctor patient relationships, the sanctity of the clubhouse culture and union concerns about privacy rights.
The dimensions and the implications of the drug issue in professional sports are just beginning to be understood.
One must understand the scope of the problem before one can devise effective policy.
Eradicating drug abuse is no simple matter.
New chemical compounds and new delivery methods (making detection much more difficult) are being developed every day.
Underscoring the intractability of the problem is the fact that most athletes under investigation in the BALCO scandal are Olympians, and that the International Olympic Committee is reputed to have the gold standard in anti doping policies.
Down the road, gene modification therapy will further complicate the landscape.
Major League Baseball must be patient and tenacious if it is to have success in the long run fight against performance enhancing drugs.
Fans, too, need patience.
US lawmakers ripped into Major League Baseball's new drug testing plan, describing it as shamefully inadequate on the eve of a Congressional hearing into rampant steroid taking by stars.
The option of imposing fines rather than mandatory bans for steroid offenses raised questions about the quality of MLB's anti doping plan as well as the trustworthiness of leaders to police the game.
Revealing weak points of the plan, US House of Representatives Government Reform Committee chairman Tom Davis and ranking minority member Henry Waxman sent an open letter to baseball commissioner Bud Selig and union boss Don Fehr.
"Our preliminary review raises questions about whether the new policy is as comprehensive and effective as ,claimed," Davis and Waxman wrote, pointing up numerous weaknesses compared with World Anti Doping Agency (WADA) standards.
"We have a number of questions about the discrepancies between Major League Baseball's public presentation of its new drug testing effort and the language of the new policy.
We hope you will come prepared to address these questions."
Major League Baseball, which presented its plan to lawmakers Monday in advance of the hearings, began steroid testing last season and unveiled a toughened plan January 13 that Selig said "will eradicate steroid use."
Despite tough talk, baseball's policy shows possible fines with no bans for any steroid offender.
First offences were stated as punishable by "a 10 day suspension or up to a 10000 dollar fine" with second offences a 30 day ban or 25000 dollar fine, then 60 day ban or 50000 dollar fine, one year ban or 100000 dollar fine.
"One hundred thousand dollars is less money than some players earn in one game," Davis and Waxman noted.
The penalty for a fifth violation is at the commissioner's discretion.
US Senator John McCain ripped Selig and Fehr in a letter for misrepresenting the standards of baseball's anti doping plan and hinted that lawmakers were ready to take action if baseball leaders would not impose mandatory bans.
"I can reach no conclusion but that the league and the players' union have misrepresented to me and to the American public the substance of MLB's new steroid policy," McCain wrote.
"I expect the league and the players' union to modify the new policy.
To do anything less than that would constitute a violation of the public's trust, a blow to the integrity of Major League Baseball and an invitation to further scrutiny of the league's steroid policy."
Steroid offenders who are fined rather than suspended are not identified under baseball's plan and even those suspended have no mandatory public confirmation the ban was for steroids, results being "strictly confidential".
Compare that to the two year public ban for steroid first offenders in Olympic sports and lifetime ban thereafter under WADA rules and it's easy to see why baseball's plan was eyed with scorn and skepticism.
"Despite the public assurances of Major League Baseball officials, we have questions about the effectiveness of its new drug policy," Davis and Waxman wrote.
"There appear to be major differences between Major League Baseball's new policy and the independent, widely respected testing program of the Olympics.
"The Olympic policy appears comprehensive, strict, independent, and transparent.
Major League Baseball's program appears to raise questions on all four counts."
The baseball policy excludes four anabolic steroids boldione, danazol, quinbolone and dihydroepiandrostone that are banned for Olympians.
"Designer" steroids covered under Olympic doping guidelines are not under baseball's plan.
"The failure of Major League Baseball to cover designer steroids would appear to be a significant omission," Davis and Waxman wrote.
"According to experts, hundreds of potential "designer" steroids already exist.
Major League Baseball is still confronting a major scandal cgation is launched into drug testing and the league and union "have successfully resisted an investigation at the trial court level" with the entire program subject to renegotiation if suspended beyond a year.
"This provision appears designed to discourage responsible independent oversight," Davis and Waxman wrote.
In a joint statement, Major League Baseball confirmed only that the draft given Monday to lawmakers was indeed the plan being used since March 3.
"We expect player ratification within days," Fehr said.
