Outside the hospice where the severely brain damaged Schiavo, 41, entered her fifth day without nutrition and hydration, a spokesman for her parents said that Schiavo was "now showing signs of starving to death."
But a lawyer for Schiavo's husband, Michael, whom a state judge granted permission to disconnect her feeding tube and let her die, said she was not suffering.
"Terri is stable, peaceful, calm," the lawyer, George Felos, said.
Legal scholars said it would be highly unusual for the Atlanta appeals court to order the feeding tube reinserted based on its analysis of Whittemore's ruling.
But the Schiavo case has surprised at every turn.
The full US 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta, Georgia, refused on Wednesday to reconsider a request to reinsert the feeding tube to a brain damaged woman in Florida, dealing another blow to hopes of her parents to keep her alive.
The 10 2 ruling came hours after a three judge panel from the appeals court ruled against the family.
The parents, Robert and Mary Schindler, suffered another setback Wednesday when the Florida legislature decided not to intervene in the struggle.
Florida Governor Jeb Bush, meanwhile, sought court permission to take custody of Terri Schiavo, 41, who was incapacitated in 1990 when her heart stopped briefly cutting oxygen to her brain.
