We can see your eyes rolling already, but bear with us: Should an inactive child use a personal trainer to become more fit and healthy?
Time was, that question might have seemed ludicrous.
But in an era of overworked (and under fit) parents, justifiable desires to keep kids from roaming neighborhood parks solo, ubiquitous butt bound digital entertainment and a habitat loaded with high calorie treats, today's kids increasingly are tomorrow's chronic disease statistics.
Approximately 30 percent of children ages 6 to 19 are overweight and 15 percent are obese, according to the American Obesity Association.
And child obesity predicts adult obesity with frightening accuracy.
But a personal trainer?
A $50 to $70 an hour luxury most of us don't even allow ourselves?
"We may lose a generation to obesity and diabetes," said Rich Salke, owner of Rich Bodies, a gym in Georgetown.
Salke works with many children, fat and fit alike, as young as 10.
Even well intentioned parents might lack the knowledge and community resources to rescue their children from the express lane to obesity, Salke said.
Other experts, including some who have no vested interest in kids' training, agree.
"The exercise professional who should have the greatest impact on public health (for children) is the personal trainer," said Walter Thompson, a kinesiology and nutrition professor at Georgia State University and an expert on personal trainer programs.
"If parents see that their child is overweight, they should consider" personal training, Thompson said.
He and others say children as young as 7 or 8 could start working with trainers.
Trainers can help kids who don't enjoy organized sports or are embarrassed doing active things with fitter kids.
You can use body mass index (BMI) to determine if your child is overweight or obese.
(Find a child BMI calculator at www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dnpa/bmi/bmi for age.htm.)
But Steven Horowitz, Maryland director of the National Strength and Conditioning Association (NSCA) and director of Velocity Sports Performance in Rockville, Md., has a simpler method: "It's pretty obvious when your kid tries to run down the block or up stairs.
If they cannot do that (because they get winded), you have a big problem."
So, okay, maybe a trainer could help your child.
But won't kids get bored by the follow the clipboard around the gym routine?
Yes, said Salke.
He frames exercises as games to keep kids interested and having fun.
One routine involves hanging a rope from the ceiling and testing kids to jump up and touch it, first with one hand, then the other.
"That builds quad power and coordination, and they love it," he said.
He has kids hurl stability balls at the ground to see how high they'll bounce, and jump back and forth over a band stretched between two points.
Salke works with individual kids and small groups, including sibling pairs.
Salke and Thompson agree that the training must be fun for the kids and that parents should pick trainers experienced with children and certified by NSCA or the American College of Sports Medicine (no group yet certifies in pediatric training).
Insist on talking to parents of other child clients.
"This can be expensive," Thompson said, "but so is the loss of income and wealth when the child becomes ill with a lifestyle related disease like Type 2 diabetes, heart disease or cancer."
Vanessa Jones' oldest child was regularly falling asleep to the television, and her youngest begged to go to Dairy Queen to get a toy advertised on TV.
Jones, a stay at home mother,, responded by banning television except on weekends.
She and her friends are increasingly concerned about children's television the commercials, the programming and the fact that kids are just sitting there instead of playing.
This weekend they are getting some help from an unlikely source: Nickelodeon, the No.1 network for children, is replacing its usual Saturday afternoon lineup with a message encouraging young viewers to go outside and play.
The move by Nick comes at a time when networks face a backlash over the potentially negative impacts of TV viewing.
High profile reports have linked television watching to childhood obesity, for example.
That has left children's networks including the No. 2 player Cartoon Network with a tricky balancing act.
After all, their revenue models depend on children watching plenty of television, which includes commercials for junk food.
They also make money when they package their characters with food products, such as Kraft's SpongeBob SquarePants macaroni and cheese, featuring the Nickelodeon character.
Marva Smalls, executive vice president for public affairs at Nickelodeon, acknowledged that awareness about childhood obesity is up, but said the network's initiatives were not a response to outside pressure.
"What's good for kids is good for business," she said.
In addition to today's programming hiatus in which there will be no kids' shows from noon to 3 p.m. Nick has sponsored "Let's Just Play" events across the country, and is awarding grants to schools to expand physical play.
The network also is working on a policy to require food products featuring Nickelodeon characters to have additional nutritional information on packaging.
The network says it will not lose significant revenue today, because it can shift the schedule to air commercials at other times.
However, Nickelodeon is investing tens of millions of dollars on the overall campaign, Smalls said.
Competitors are likely to follow suit.
The Cartoon Network, owned by Turner Broadcasting System, said it plans to roll out its own program targeting childhood obesity soon.
"We are working on a long term program to deal with this issue but we don't have all of the elements in place," said spokeswoman Laurie Goldberg.
Some critics are skeptical about how effective the networks' efforts will be.
"If they really want to address childhood obesity, they would stop marketing junk food to kids," said Susan Linn, author of "Consuming Kids: The Hostile Takeover of Childhood" and associate director of the media center at Judge Baker Children's Center in Boston.
"I think what they are concerned about is regulation," she said.
Margo Wootan, director of nutrition policy at the Center for Science in the Public Interest, expects media companies' efforts to be "measured and just enough to keep the government and courts off their backs."
But Jones applauds Nickelodeon for today's effort.
"Having something like that, if they are willing to make a sacrifice even for three hours, that makes me willing to put up with some of the other things," she said.
Cynthia Ziegler, a mother of two, said, "At least they are doing something."
Ziegler allows her 7 year old daughter and 8 year old son to watch television only on weekends.
A number of high profile reports about the media's role in childhood obesity have been issued in the last year, including: The Institute of Medicine this week published a report commissioned by Congress that called for more voluntary industry regulation of marketing to children.
The American Psychological Association issued a report in February, saying marketing to kids under 9 is inherently deceptive.
A Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation report, also released in February, suggested a variety of actions, from reducing the time children spend with television to increasing the media messages promoting fitness and sound nutrition.
The Center for Science in the Public Interest came out with a report in November 2003 that claims excessive television viewing contributes to childhood obesity and calls for stricter regulations on advertising.
In Congress, several pieces of legislation aiming to limit marketing to children have been proposed.
And more litigation is likely, said John Banzhaf, a law professor at George Washington University and a proponent for using the courts to make industry more responsible on childhood obesity issues.
At a conference this summer on obesity litigation, sponsored by the Public Health Advocacy Institute, Banzhaf heard discussion about suing media companies that air misleading junk food commercials, as well as the food companies themselves.
"If we could go after Nickelodeon, the impact would be greater" than winning lawsuits against food companies, he said.
Smalls acknowledged that Nickelodeon is in the business of selling advertising.
"Ice cream, candy, cookies are a part of kids' lives," the network executive said.
However, Nickelodeon also is committed to providing nutritional information to families, she said, on television as well as its Web site, magazines and sponsored local events.
Caroline Wilbert writes for The Atlanta Journal Constitution.
