Don't smoke, especially if you're pregnant.
(Recent studies show that intrauterine exposure to inhaled smoke produces a dose dependent increase in the weight of children, beginning at adolescence.)
Former US president Bill Clinton went to a Manhattan school Tuesday to announce a 10 year initiative to combat childhood obesity.
Clinton, who is recovering from quadruple bypass surgery and had to overcome his affinity for junk food, described the weight problem as a national epidemic and stressed that something had to be done to change the eating habits of America's young people.
The initiative, a partnership with the American Heart Association, will include working with the food and restaurant industry to promote change, increasing physical activity and nutrition at schools nationwide, said the former president.
The initiative also aims at creating a campaign to engage kids in making better choices and providing their parents with information on how to incorporate heart healthy activities and diets into their family routines.
"I feel so strongly about this," said Clinton, whose interest in the subject stems from his recent heart surgery.
He said he was alerted by the substantial numbers of children with so called adult onset diabetes, simply due to their eating and exercise habits.
Recent reports indicate that nearly half of the city's elementary students are overweight.
More than twice as many kids are overweight as in 1980, and overweight children and teens have a 70 percent chance of becoming overweight adults.
Lawmakers think Texas schoolchildren better shape up, and they don't just mean in reading, writing and arithmetic.
These kids need to lose some weight.
Citing childhood obesity as a serious problem, bills in the Legislature propose increasing the required physical education classes from three times a week to five times a week for students in kindergarten through ninth grade.
"If we don't make them healthier when they're young, it's very hard to reverse that when they're older," said state Rep Martha Wong, R Houston, who wrote House Bill 2785.
State Sen Jane Nelson, R Lewisville, filed similar legislation, Senate Bill 42.
"We are starting to see the consequences of de emphasizing basic health and nutrition in our schools in the form of chronic diseases caused by obesity and illness," Nelson said.
"We only get one body in this lifetime, and we need to make sure that our children know how to take care of it."
Becky Watts, spokeswoman for the Illinois State Board of Education, said Illinois is the only state that requires daily physical activity for public school students.
But government is increasingly recognizing obesity as a health threat.
The Internal Revenue Service made weight loss treatment tax deductible in 2002, and last year, Medicare officially recognized obesity as a disease and started evaluating which weight loss treatments the program would cover.
Wong said that she has a lot of support for her bill requiring more physical education but that she's heard some concerns from middle school officials who already have a tight schedule.
Cecil Floyd, the association's executive director, said many middle schools reduced physical education because the Legislature required them to do so much else.
"There's just a whole lot of courses being required at the middle school, and there's just no time to offer other classes," he said.
But Floyd agrees that children need more exercise.
One out of three Texas schoolchildren is overweight or severely overweight, according to the Texas Department of Agriculture.
It's a serious problem, said Judith Stern, vice president of the American Obesity Association, in Washington, D.C. "They can be setting up a pattern for life," she said.
"If a fat kid becomes a fat adolescent, they're more than likely to become a fat adult."
State Rep Ryan Guillen, D Rio Grande City, filed a bill to make sure schools don't cheat on meeting their physical education requirements.
House Bill 517 forbids schools to count time spent walking to and from class and the school bus as physical activity.
Other bills address obesity, such as Senate Bill 205, which would put students' body mass index on their report cards.
Senate Bill 1379 encourages more stringent school nutrition policies than the federal government demands Lisa Wheeler, the P.E. teacher at Oaklawn Elementary School in Fort Worth, said her school has physical education classes five times a week, and she tries to make it count because students don't seem to have the energy or stamina they had when she started teaching 15 years ago.
"It seems like before, they had been a lot more active,They tend to stay inside, and when they stay inside they tend to watch TV, play video games and eat junk food," Wheeler said.
Rene Walker, a Fort Worth mother, said she sees the same problem with her children.
Her youngest is in high school, and she has to encourage him to eat better and stay active.
"Oh God, it's chips and Coke, I swear that's all he eats," she said.
"I have to kick him out the door periodically because all he wants to do is watch TV and play video games."
But the system is also to blame, she said, because children are required to stay at their desks in school for so much testing.
"I think parents feel like there is a lot of emphasis on testing and performing well in school, and there's so much pressure on the kids," said Walker, who is president of the Fort Worth Council of PTAs.
"When you're sitting in a desk all day and you don't have much release, that's very stressful for kids."
