Pope John Paul II, who famously quipped that he would not know where to address a letter of resignation, revealed in his final testament that he considered stepping aside in 2000.
"I hope that He will help me to recognize how long I must continue this service," the testament reads.
"May the mercy of God give me the necessary strength for this service."
"According to the designs of Providence, I was given to live in the difficult century that is beginning to recede into the past," he wrote in March 2000.
"And now, in the year that will see my life reach the 80s, I must ask myself if the time has come to repeat with Simon in the Bible 'nunc dimittis'" the start of a phrase that translates as "Lord, lettest now Thy servant depart in peace according to Thy Word."
At the time, John Paul II's walk had begun to slow, his stoop was becoming more pronounced, and he was increasingly showing the symptoms of Parkinson's disease, which was already preventing him from speaking clearly on occasion.
The writing came two months after Karl Lehmann, the bishop of Mainz, Germany, sparked a row by intimating that John Paul II might consider stepping down if he felt that he could no longer carry out his duties, and that the Roman Catholic Church needed "a strong man, a leader."
John Paul II made what was seen as an indirect reference to the remarks when he said at the time: "God never asks us anything beyond our forces.
He gives us the strength to accomplish what he expects from us."
But in a letter marking the UN International Old People's Year in 1999 he wrote: "In spite of the limits imposed by age, I still have a taste for life.
