Rambling and threatening letters from the man believed to be the killer of a federal judge's husband and mother prompted the Illinois Attorney General's office to investigate him six years ago, former state officials say.
Investigators went to the Chicago home of Bart Ross in the winter of 1999 and created an extensive file on him, noting his paranoia and anger at the government and judiciary, said a former investigator and the office's one time chief of investigations.
Ross, 57, an unemployed electrician, committed suicide Wednesday in a Milwaukee suburb after a police officer pulled him over because of broken taillights on his van.
After Ross killed himself, authorities found a note implicating himself in the murders of Michael Lefkow, 64, and Donna Humphrey, 89.
They were the husband and mother of Judge Joan Lefkow.
"It pains me to think we had this guy in front of us six years ago with no idea what evil he was destined to do," said Kerry Polizzi, a former investigator for the attorney general's office.
Daniel Callahan, a former chief of investigations for the office, said that although he knew of the threats Ross made, it is difficult to fault the actions of the investigators at the time.
"There was nothing in the correspondence that led us to believe there was going to be violence," Callahan said.
Polizzi said the attorney general's office receives as many as 100 alarm raising letters each year.
Ross had been treated for cancer at the University of Illinois Chicago Hospital from 1992 to 1995 and spent more than a decade attempting to receive damages for what he said was medical malpractice that had disfigured his face.
Lefkow, a federal judge, had dismissed the most recent of his repeated lawsuits last year.
Ross "was concerned about government conspiracies, his civil rights, and even accused the hospital of putting a transmitter in his mouth," Polizzi said.
He wrote sometimes incoherent letters to officials at various levels of government.
"There was a file on this, and they received threats from him before," said Dan Curry, who had been press secretary to then Attorney General James Ryan at the time of the 1999 investigation.
Curry said he couldn't recall which other public officials received direct threats.
A man who shot himself to death during a traffic stop in Wisconsin claimed in a suicide note that he killed a federal judge's husband and mother in Chicago, a source close to the investigation told The Associated Press Thursday.
