An out of work electrician whose delusional, decade long legal crusade against doctors, lawyers and the government was dismissed last year by a federal judge killed himself Wednesday night, leaving behind letters in which he admitted murdering the judge's husband and mother here last week.
Bart A. Ross, 57, had sued the federal government and a raft of others for $1 billion, saying they persecuted him with "Nazi style" and terrorist tactics as he pursued a medical malpractice claim stemming from the severe disfigurement of his cancerous jaw.
He left a suicide note in the van where he had been living, confessing to the crime, and, in a letter to a local television station, said he had planned to assassinate the judge, Joan Humphrey Lefkow of U.S. District Court, but "had no choice but to shoot" her loved ones when they discovered him hiding in the basement.
Along with the confessional suicide note, the police said they found some 300 .22 caliber bullets, the same caliber used in the execution style slayings, in the Plymouth van where Ross, who had no criminal record, shot himself in the head after being stopped in a Milwaukee suburb for a missing taillight.
Though the authorities said they would not consider the case closed until they could tie Ross, through fingerprints and DNA, to physical evidence left at the scene, his death and admissions were a shocking turn in a vast investigation that had thus far focused on white supremacists.
Chicago Police Superintendent Philip J. Cline said Thursday that Ross' name was on a list of people, culled from Lefkow's caseload, that investigators planned to interview.
He also said Ross resembled one of two composite sketches released two days after the deaths, and that his account of leaving the Lefkows' home at 1:15 p.m. on Feb 28 matched witness reports.
Lefkow, who expressed "sincere empathy" for Ross in legal papers even as she said his claims "lack any possible merit," described him in an interview early Thursday as "a very pathetic, tragic person" and said the news was "very chilling."
"I guess on one level I'm relieved that it didn't have anything to do with the white supremacy movement, because I feel my children are going to be safer," Lefkow said as she departed for Denver to bury her mother, Donna Humphrey.
"It's heartbreaking that my husband and mother had to die over something like this."
The man believed to have killed a federal judge's husband and mother typed out a suicide letter two weeks before the shootings and included a hit list of judges, lawyers and doctors, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
Bart Ross, 57, an unemployed electrician, committed suicide March 9 in his van in a Milwaukee suburb.
In the van, police and federal agents found the letter in which he implicated himself in the Feb 28 murders of Michael Lefkow, 64, the husband of U.S. District Judge Joan Lefkow, and the judge's mother, Donna Humphrey, 89.
"When you read this I should be dead, so I am writing in past tense," he wrote in the four page letter obtained by the Chicago Tribune.
The typed letter, dated Feb 13, was found along with a handwritten account of the Lefkow killings, the newspaper said.
The account detailed how he was hiding in the Lefkows' basement when Michael Lefkow discovered him and how he killed both victims.
He expressed regret for killing Lefkow and Humphrey because "they personally did to me no wrong," he wrote.
The letter declared Ross a victim of medical malpractice and contained a hit list of seven federal judges, four state judges, 10 lawyers and five doctors, according to the newspaper.
Ross, a heavy smoker, was treated for cancer of the mouth from 1992 to 1995.
Surgery and radiation saved his life but disfigured his face, and Ross set out through the court system trying to make his doctors pay for what they'd done.
Lefkow had dismissed the most recent of his repeated lawsuits last year.
"I was left with no possibility to live my life, but to progressively suffer more and more, so like those who jumped down from the WTC Towers on September 11, 2001, I 'jumped' too.
On the way, I intended to send to Hell as many of the listed (expletive) as I was lucky to get," Ross wrote, according to the Tribune.
"I am not a murderer," he wrote in the letter.
"The murderers are the listed (expletive), who violated me like Nazis and terrorists and deprived me justice and compensation to put my life in order, and in this way deprived me possibility of salvaging my life."
Nine days after the Lefkows were killed, a police officer in West Allis, Wis. stopped the van Ross was driving because a taillight was broken, and Ross shot himself in the head.
Hours earlier, a parking ticket was issued for his minivan about four blocks from a federal courthouse in Milwaukee where two federal judges who upheld dismissals of Ross' lawsuits have offices.
One of the judges was on Ross' hit list, the Tribune reported.
Ross ended his suicide letter saying he wanted to cause pain to everyone on his list.
"I regret that I cannot torture this (expletive) the way they tortured me for over 12 1/2 years and I regret that I cannot at least send them all to Hell," he wrote.
The investigation into the execution style slaying of a Chicago federal judges husband and mother took a surprising turn Thursday when police said that a man who killed himself during a traffic stop was now a prime suspect.
Suspicion had earlier been focused on a neo Nazi and white supremacist group whose leader had previously threatened the 61 year old judge.
Police have identified the suspect as Bart Ross, a loner with no apparent links to the white supremacist group.
Attorney Michael Lefkow, 64, and Donna Grace Humphrey, 89, were discovered by district court judge Joan Lefkow in her suburban Edgewater home after she returned from work on February 28.
Both had been shot in the head in the basement of the house.
Earlier on Thursday, a local television station received a rambling, handwritten note signed Bart A. Ross in which the writer confessed to killing Lefkow and Humphrey.
It arrived in the newsroom after a man identified as Bart Ross shot himself when his brown minivan was pulled over Wednesday in a Milwaukee suburb about 130 kilometers (80 miles) north of where the slaying took place.
Chicago police said a note was discovered in the vehicle in which Ross implicated himself in the murder.
In the letter addressed to the television station, the writer said that he broke into the Lefkow home because he wanted "to get Judge Lefkow and them others, whoever I could get."
According to the authorities, Judge Lefkow had dismissed a medical malpractice suit filed by Ross a number of years ago.
After he was discovered in his hiding spot in the utility room, the author of the letter said he "had no choice" but to shoot Michael Lefkow in the back of the head.
He then went on to describe shooting Humphrey after she called out "Michael, Michael" and came looking for her son in law at the sound of the shots.
The author gave several reasons why he wanted to kill the judge.
"Judge Lefkow was No. 1 to kill because she finished me off and deprived me to live my life through outrageous abuse of judicial power and decicration (sic) of the judicial office.
Judge Lefkow, to her neighbors, is a church going 'angel'.
To me, Judge Lefkow is a Nazi style criminal and terrorist," the author wrote.
The writer also mentioned two other people he intended to kill in retribution for the problems hed had with the medical malpractice suit.
Police said they have not yet confirmed that Ross was the killer.
"We understand that there is plenty of information out there pointing to this individual as a possible offender," said Chicago Police Superintendent Philip Cline.
"However, only a complete and total analysis of all the evidence will point us in any one direction."
The killer broke into U.S. District Judge Joan H. Lefkow's house and hid in a utility closet.
Furious that she had rejected his rambling lawsuit, he planned to wait until she came home and then shoot her dead.
But the judge's husband found the man first.
"I had no choice ,but to shoot him," Bart Ross wrote in a suicide note received Thursday by a Chicago television station.
"Then I heard a voice, 'Michael, Michael,' so I looked to the hallway ,and saw an older woman.
I had to shoot her, too.
"I followed with a second shot to the head in both cases to minimize their suffering."
Chicago police announced Thursday that Ross, who killed himself with a single shot to the head in a Milwaukee suburb Wednesday night, is responsible for the Feb 28 killings of Lefkow's husband, Michael, and mother, Dorothy Humphrey, a case that sent shudders through the federal judiciary.
Late Thursday night a Chicago police spokesman confirmed that Ross's DNA matched evidence found in the Lefkows' house.
Police Superintendent Phil Cline told reporters that letters left by the electrician, 57, contained details only the killer would know.
He also said a witness saw someone resembling Ross leaving the North Chicago house on the day of the shootings.
But Cline emphasized that police are not prepared to make a definitive statement about all aspects of the case until the evidence has been analyzed.
"This case is by no means closed," he said.
