Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili on Tuesday called for a new Yalta conference, a voluntary association of new European democracies whose goal would be to extend the rule of liberty throughout the Black Sea region and beyond.
In an editorial column in The Washington Post, Saakashvili said the diplomatic agreement reached at Yalta after World War II by the United States, Britain and Russia "relegated millions of people to a ruthless tyranny."
He said the division of Europe created at Yalta and the Iron Curtain that marked its boundary were history, with much of the territory allocated to Russian leader Josef Stalin now democratic nations.
"After recent discussions with Presidents Traian Basescu of Romania and Viktor Yushchenko of Ukraine," Saakashvili said, "I believe it is time for a new Yalta Conference" with three main goals.
He said nations must work together to consolidate democracy in the region, and said Georgia achieved it only 18 months ago.
But Saakashvili said two regions of Georgia South Ossetia and Abkhazia "remain untouched by the freedom the rest of Georgia enjoys.
We can and must resolve these disputes to better the lives of Georgians."
He also said other nations in the region must work towards democracy.
"Moldova, like Georgia, faces a separatist region that maintains itself with cast off Soviet weaponry and the profits from an illicit economy based on trafficking in weapons, drugs and women," Saakashvili said.
"These are the last razor sharp splinters of the Soviet empire."
Saakashvili said the world can do more to aid the people of Belarus in their qeust for freedom.
"The new Yalta conference will press for liberty in Belarus through increased travel restrictions on government officials, expanded financial and material support to the opposition and enhanced training for civic society in the methods of peaceful protests that helped free the people of Ukraine and Georgia," he said.
A new Yalta conference should seek to expand the frontiers of freedom far beyond the Black Sea, he said, mentioning Cuba, Zimbabwe and Burma.
"It is time to return to Yalta."
Saakashvili said.
"This time we will not engage in a secret diplomacy in which our values are compromised and our people enslaved.
In this new association of democracies, our diplomacy will be open ,and we will begin to make Yalta a symbol of hope ."
Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili, attending a major military parade celebrating independence Thursday, called on two separatist regions in the ex Soviet republic to end their isolation and reunite.
Against the backdrop of a march past by 10000 soldiers through the centre of the capital Tbilisi, Saakashvili told the people of Abkhazia, on the Black Sea coast, and South Ossetia, at the foot of the Caucasus mountains, that their future lay within Georgia.
"Nothing separates us.
All that we have, including this army, is also yours.
The time of isolation is over.
We must live together," Saakashvili said.
Saakashvili said Georgia would only "be fully free" when independence day celebrations also took place in Sukhumi, capital of Abkhazia, which like South Ossetia ousted Georgian authorities in separatist wars in the early 1990s after the Soviet collapse.
"I promise you that will happen," he said.
Saakashvili, who came to power in the "rose revolution" of 2003, has made reuniting Georgia a central theme of his presidency.
However, the Russian backed rebel leaderships in Abkhazia and South Ossetia are adamant that they are independent from Tbilisi.
Georgia's army is widely considered too small and poorly trained to retake either region by force, although units being trained by US military advisors were prominent in the Tbilisi parade.
Georgian officials frequently complain about Russian support for the separatist republics.
Saakashvili said in his speech that he wanted "friendly, but equal relations" with Moscow.
High ranking officials from Georgia and the separatist region of Abkhazia met with a United Nations envoy Thursday to discuss security issues in the tense region.
The meeting between Georgian Minister for Conflict Resolution Georgy Khaindrava and Abkhazia's foreign minister, Sergei Shamba, took place in the Gali district, which is patrolled by U.N. monitors.
It was to focus on such themes as cooperation between law enforcement authorities, minimizing bellicose propaganda and providing maps pinpointing the location of minefields to a British de mining organization, the Interfax news agency reported.
The participants agreed to meet again in mid June, and they agreed to establish a joint group to investigate reports of cease fire violations, Interfax said.
Abkhazia has run its own affairs since 1993, when separatists drove out Georgian government troops.
The Black Sea region is not recognized internationally, but has cultivated closer ties with Russia.
Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili has vowed to bring Abkhazia and another separatist region, South Ossetia, back under Tbilisi's rule.
U.S. President George W. Bush expressed support for Saakashvili's policy on the regions during his visit to Tbilisi earlier this week, saying Georgia's territorial integrity must be respected.
The International Red Cross said Thursday that it would end most food aid to needy Abkhazians because the humanitarian situation in the region was improving.
The group currently gives monthly and quarterly food parcels and hot meals to more than 13000 Abkhazian residents.
It will provide quarterly aid to some families while providing others with the opportunity for training in agriculture, commerce or a craft.
President George W. Bush and US backed President Mikhail Saakashvili on Tuesday discussed Tbilisi's handling of political reforms and its prickly pro Russian separatist regions, the White House said.
Bush also reiterated "our condolences on last week's death of the prime minister, who was a champion of freedom," spokesman Scott McClellan said, referring to the February 3 demise of Zurab Zhvania.
"The two presidents had a good discussion about Georgia's ongoing efforts to advance democratic reforms, to fight corruption and to expand freedom for the Georgian people," McClellan told reporters.
"They also discussed the Georgian government's serious settlement plan to resolve its separatist conflict in south Ossetia by peaceful means," he said.
Zhvania had been the key interlocutor with Russia over Abkhazia and South Ossetia, two separatist regions that the president has promised to bring back under Tbilisi's control.
Last summer, fighting broke out on the border between Georgia and South Ossetia between Georgian and Ossetian forces.
"The two leaders underscored their commitment to deepen our country's cooperation in pursuit of freedom, prosperity and peace, in the region and beyond," said McClellan.
Two Georgian police officers have been abducted in South Ossetia in what Georgian authorities described Thursday as an attempt to sabotage the peace process with the separatist region.
The two officers, Lado Chalauri and Gochi Gvimradze, were taken hostage by an armed group in the village of Ergneti, on the administrative border between South Ossetia and Georgia.
The governor of the Georgian border region of Chida Kartli, Mikhail Kareli, told AFP that the two officers had been taken to a detention centre in Tskhinvali, the major city of South Ossetia, and the abduction was designed to disrupt peace talks with the separatist region.
"The abduction of the Georgian police officers is a provocation by the government of (South Ossetian president) Eduard Kokoity," Kareli said.
"This crime was committed when Georgian authorities and non government organisations are examining the question of a new statute for South Ossetia which could bring an end to the conflict and bring peace to the people of the region".
The head of Georgia's Security Council, Guela Bejouachvili, said security forces were conducting intense negotiations with their Ossetian counterparts to free the two police officers as soon as possible.
The Georgian government was expected to meet soon and the worsening of the situation in the conflict zone with South Ossetia would be one of the main items on the agenda, officials said.
Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili said on January 12 he would present official proposals to the separatist and Russian backed territories of South Ossetia and Abkhazia by the end of this month.
Abkhazia fought a civil war against Georgia with the help of Russian mercenaries in the 1990s, and it remains a de facto Russian protectorate.
Both the government and the opposition reject its incorporation into Georgia.
South Ossetia also fought a brief war with Tbilisi in the early 1990s.
Moscow has sent peacekeeping troops to the region and has granted most of the region's ethnic Ossetian residents Russian citizenship.
Brought to power by a peaceful "rose revolution" one year ago, Saakashvili has set reuniting his country as his most urgent priority.
Around 100 people, including family and friends of the two hostages, gathered Thursday morning in front of the Ergneti border post, demanding the authorities take action to free the hostages.
The Hotel Iveria, a Soviet era showpiece on prime Tbilisi real estate, is an empty hulk, the wind whistling through its glassless windows.
For Georgia, that's a sign of progress.
For the past decade, the 20 story hotel on the capital's main avenue, commanding a stunning vista of mountains and valleys, had been a slum with a view: It was jammed with more than 1000 refugees from one of the separatist wars that keep the Caucasus region in sporadic turmoil.
Then a developer bought the refugees out for US$7000 (euro5485) a room in order to redevelop the hotel for the upmarket guest trade.
But many refugees complained the payoff wouldn't buy them suitable replacement housing.
One problem dispensed with, another created.
It's a pattern characterizing much of Georgia's effort to pull itself out of the abyss of poverty and corruption it had plunged into under longtime leader Eduard Shevardnadze, who was ousted in the "Rose Revolution" protests of November 2003.
His reform oriented successor, Mikhail Saakashvili, was inaugurated on Jan 25, 2004.
Now comes the death of Prime Minister Zurab Zhvania, who had been in office slightly less than a year when he succumbed to apparent carbon monoxide poisoning by a faulty space heater, and new anxieties have arisen about Georgia's prospects for real change.
What would seem a preposterous way for a high ranking official to die in a developed country doesn't necessarily seem far fetched in Tbilisi, where the central heating system has been out for a decade.
But neither is the official explanation entirely accepted by Georgians.
It reflects the lingering distrust of a government many of whose members served under Shevardnadze, says Georgian political analyst Davit Usupashvili.
Some of the transformations over the past year have been unambiguously positive: long delayed salaries for teachers and civil servants have been paid, highways once infamous for wheel eating potholes are under repair, military restructuring has boosted the once ragged armed forces' confidence.
"They've accomplished a remarkable amount," U.S. Ambassador Richard Miles said of the government's moves, adding praise of moves to purge government agencies of unproductive bureaucrats.
Some other moves are a matter of going forward at an oblique tack.
Georgia and Russia have agreed to restore rail links, severed since the conflict over Georgia's breakaway northwest region of Abkhazia.
But with Abkhazia still refusing to countenance possible reintegration into Georgia, the trains will skirt Abkhazia by taking to the Black Sea on ferries.
Initial satisfaction over a series of well publicized arrests in a war on corruption and criminal gangs darkened after many of those arrested were allowed to avoid prison terms by refunding what they allegedly stole.
The practice was censured this year by the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe, the continent's top human rights body, dealing a blow to the respect widely accorded to Saakashvili's reformist government.
"The government should say an absolute 'no' to the absolute abuse of power," said analyst Usupashvili.
But Miles said one could argue that the system has its merits, especially given the still shaky court system.
"It doesn't fit exactly with the rule of law," the ambassador said, but added that it may work better than submitting cases to "a judicial process that might or might not prove successful."
Abkhazia isn't the only restive corner of this South Carolina sized country of 5 million.
Adzharia and South Ossetia have also proved problematic.
One of the new government's most notable early successes was reasserting control over Adzharia, an autonomous region whose feudal style leader, Aslan Abashidze, had defied Tbilisi and withheld tax revenues for years.
Abashidze's decision to blow up bridges into Adzharia, supposedly to forestall a Georgian invasion, galvanized Adzharians' long simmering dissatisfaction with him.
But although Abashidze essentially drove himself out of office, his downfall appeared to make the Georgian authorities confident that South Ossetia could be brought to heel just as easily.
Instead, South Ossetian and Georgian forces launched into a brief but intense spasm of fighting, and South Ossetia is now figuring in the rumors and conspiracy theories surrounding the strange death of Prime Minister Zhvania.
Zhvania had been pushing for a negotiated settlement, which could include an offer of autonomy apparently similar to that in Adzharia which so irritated Tbilisi.
Some have claimed to see the hand of Georgia's giant neighbor, Russia, which has powerful interests in a neighbor that also is close to oil fields, and abuts both war torn Chechnya and NATO member Turkey.
The Kremlin has sharply dismissed these suspicions.
Georgian officials, while insisting Zhvania's death was an accident, have brought in the FBI to investigate.
Usupashvili, the analyst, declined to say whether he believed the official explanation for Zhvania's death but noted that the authorities who made it "are well known for signing false statements in the past."
Twelve residents of Georgia's separatist republic of South Ossetia were abducted Saturday by kidnappers seeking the release of a Georgian police officer seized three days earlier in the region, authorities in Tbilisi and in South Ossetia said.
One of the 12, identified as Makhar Gassyev, a member of the South Ossetia's self declared "government", was released later in the day, according to pictures shown on Georgian television.
The 12 were seized in Ergneti, near the border between South Ossetia and the rest of Georgia, by kidnappers demanding the release of policeman Lado Chalauri.
Chalauri and another Georgian policeman, Gochi Gvimradze, were kidnapped Wednesday night, also in Ergneti, but Gvimradze was later released following negotiations.
"We will do all we can to prevent an escalation of violence from taking place.
But Georgian authorities will never exchange the Georgian policeman for the Ossetian delinquents," said the head of Georgia's National Security Council, Guela Bejouachvili.
Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili was to attend an emergency meeting of the national security council to discuss the crisis.
"We will not release the hostages until the Georgian policeman is freed," one of the kidnappers told Georgian television.
"Otherwise, we will block all roads leading to Tskhinvali," the major city of South Ossetia, "and we will keep hold of the hostages."
Russia's foreign ministry Saturday demanded the release of the 12 hostages, warning in a statement of "escalation of the conflict" between Tblisi and South Ossetia.
