The Washington power broker is considered one of Kerry's closest confidants.
But a large scale accounting scandal at Fannie Mae could dim Johnson's prospects unless it's resolved soon.
A Fannie Mae scandal could block another possible candidate for Treasury, Franklin Raines, Clinton's White House budget director and the current CEO of Fannie Mae.
Democrats point to Roger Altman, deputy Treasury secretary in the Clinton administration (even though he was a bit player in the Whitewater saga), or New York Times reporter turned investment banker Steven Rattner, as two other front runners.
There's less talk and even more of a question mark about the second tier Cabinet posts, although some names have been bandied about: Rep Richard Gephardt as a possible Labor secretary and former Clinton Environmental Protection Agency director Carol Browner as Interior secretary.
After hemming and hawing and bobbing and weaving, the board of directors of Fannie Mae finally jettisoned Franklin D. Raines, the mortgage finance giant's former chief executive, and Timothy Howard, its former chief financial officer, last week.
They appear to have done so only under duress from Fannie's chief regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, which in September put the company on notice that its improper accounting had vastly overstated profits and misrepresented its financial position.
The board's reluctance to defenestrate Raines and Howard, who appear to have misstated their company's financial statements to the tune of around $9 billion, fed suspicions that Fannie Mae's directors were loyal to management first, and shareholders second.
Questions of allegiance were also raised when it became clear that Fannie's directors allowed Raines to retire rather than to be fired outright.
That distinction means that he will reap millions of dollars in benefits and stock awards that he may otherwise have lost.
