The directors of Fannie Mae, the big mortgage finance company, will meet Sunday to consider the fate of two senior executives who signed off on financial statements that violated accounting rules, people close to the company said Friday.
The two executives, Franklin D. Raines, the chairman and chief executive, and J. Timothy Howard, the chief financial officer, certified financial statements that the Securities and Exchange Commission on Wednesday ordered to be restated because of significant violations in accounting rules over their treatment of derivatives and prepaid loans.
Fannie Mae said in November that a restatement would force it to recognize $9 billion in losses over the last three and a half years, wiping out more than a third of its profits over that period.
Regulators could also force the company to raise its capital levels by billions of dollars, either by selling some of the mortgages it holds in its portfolio or through a securities offering.
As it has in recent days, the company again Friday declined to issue a statement from the directors about how it intended to proceed.
But people close to the company said Raines was seeking a vote of confidence from the board Sunday as he struggles to survive the crisis.
Raines, whose senior management team has come under withering criticism by the company's main regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, testified to Congress two months ago that he expected to be held accountable by Fannie Mae's directors and shareholders if his interpretation of the accounting rules was set aside by the commission.
Long a formidable political power in Washington, Fannie Mae's support has eroded in recent months both because of the conclusions of regulators and because of the growing effectiveness of rival financial institutions.
Raines, who led the Office of Management and Budget at the White House under President Bill Clinton, has lately appeared to have lost much of the support he had from Republicans.
And in recent days, some prominent Democrats have accused the company of being mismanaged and have demanded that Raines return the tens of millions of dollars he has received in bonuses.
If directors decide to remove Raines, the selection of a successor would be politically tricky.
Candidates would need significant credibility in a city that is dominated at both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue by Republicans, particularly as the company faces the virtually inevitable prospect of new legislation and tighter regulation.
But they would also have to be committed to the company's affordable housing goals, which are often identified with Democratic lawmakers.
The decision on Raines' successor would ultimately fall to the board of the company, although administration officials could play an important role in recommending or vetoing choices, particularly since the company is in a more vulnerable position.
Among the names circulating in governmental circles on Friday to succeed Raines was Robert B. Zoellick, the U.S. trade representative.
He has worked at Fannie Mae twice before, including one stint in the 1990s when he was a senior executive in charge of its affordable housing business as well as its legal affairs and governmental relations offices.
Zoellick has also been said to be on the short list of contenders to be the next head of the World Bank.
For the last two months, Franklin D. Raines has been the public face of Fannie Mae, testifying before Congress that he believed that the company's accounting methods were sound.
Now his jobs are being taken over by two men who are respected within the company but who are not well known to outsiders.
Raines, who was chief executive and chairman, has been succeeded by two members of the company's board.
Daniel H. Mudd, Fannie Mae's vice chairman and chief operating officer, will become the company's acting chief executive.
Stephen B. Ashley, a real estate executive of the Mortgage Bankers Association, will become Fannie Mae's acting chairman.
Fannie Mae also named another executive, Robert Levin, as its interim chief financial officer, to succeed J. Timothy Howard, who, like Raines, was forced out Tuesday.
Industry specialists say that Mudd and Ashley bring different skills to guide Fannie Mae through perhaps the most challenging period in its history.
Mudd joined Fannie Mae in February 2000 after nearly a decade at GE Capital, where he rose through the management ranks.
He is known as a straight shooter with in depth knowledge of Fannie Mae's business.
What he lacks, however, are the strong political connections that made Raines such a powerful force on Capitol Hill.
"Political savvy has not been his expertise.
He's basically been invisible at Fannie," said Bert Ely, a financial industry consultant who is a longtime critic of the company.
"He's what I call the chief inside guy the guy who makes things run every day.
"A lot of Fannie's challenge right now is keeping the ship afloat and moving ahead," Ely added, "and he's better positioned than anybody on the board."
Jeffrey Sonnenfeld, an associate dean at the Yale School of Management, said of Mudd: "He's a very strong, solid player.
He knows his stuff."
Sonnenfeld added: "He is also known for being more direct.
You don't want any ambiguity as to what is known and what is not known."
Mudd has provided leadership amid economic turmoil before, managing GE Capital's Asia Pacific division through the Asian financial crisis in the late 1990s.
He also was an officer in the U.S. Marines and was decorated for combat service in Beirut, Lebanon.
Ashley, who founded the Ashley Group, a large commercial and residential real estate company with properties in New York and Connecticut, has had significant experience both in mortgage lending and in Washington politics.
A former president of the Mortgage Bankers Association, a trade group, he testified in front of a Congressional Housing Subcommittee in 1991 in support of Fannie Mae.
Mudd and Ashley have contributed to many political candidates, including several Republicans, according to federal election filings.
"It can hardly be overlooked that, as a Republican Congress is about to undertake a harsh inspection of the company, Fannie Mae is removing Raines and Howard, two men with an apparent preference for Democratic politicians, and elevating Mudd and Ashley, two men who support Republicans," said Jonathan Koppell, a professor at Yale University who has studied the politics of the company.
Ely, the financial industry consultant, said: "This is just the start of a process of cleaning things up.
Fannie Mae has a lot of work ahead."
The announcement late Tuesday night came after a series of discussions over the last few days as board members debated Raines' future at Fannie Mae.
