The images left an indelible mark on the American conscience: man's best friend wandering the abandoned streets of New Orleans or stranded atop the city's flooded houses.
But the plight of pets in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina did more than just soften the hearts of the nation's animal lovers it opened their wallets.
Tens of millions of dollars an unprecedented amount compared with other disasters, animal welfare advocates say poured into pet charities such as the Humane Society, the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, PetSmart Charities and Noah's Wish, a group whose sole purpose is to save animals during disasters.
"The images were compelling," said Wayne Pacelle, president and chief executive officer for the Humane Society of the United States.
"It was gut wrenching for people to see pets being taken away from their owners as they were being evacuated."
The overwhelming majority of post hurricane recovery and relief funds went to help people, said Katya Andresen, vice president of marketing for Network For Good, the nation's largest clearinghouse for online charitable giving.
She noted that $1.3 billion of the $2 billion raised so far for Katrina relief went to the Red Cross, primarily through the Red Cross Web site, phone lines and direct mail campaign.
Likewise, Red Cross was the top recipient of Katrina relief donations through Network For Good, with $7.5 million.
But four others in the top 10 specialize in animal assistance.
"One of the things that got a lot of (media) coverage was people having to leave their pets behind," Andresen said.
"People really connected with that part of the story and those images."
In contrast, she said, "The last big disaster was tsunami, and pets were not part of that story."
Donations reflected that.
Among the animal welfare organizations that took in the most post hurricane money were the Humane Society, with $20 million in donations, Noah's Wish, with $6.5 million, and PetSmart Charities, with $3.5 million.
Much of the money has paid or will pay for food, medical attention and vaccines, sheltering pets and reuniting them with owners, and rebuilding damaged animal shelters in Louisiana.
"People to a great extent can take care of themselves.
They can ask for help or use their cell phones, and animals cannot do that," said Terri Crisp, founder and director of Noah's Wish.
"People's hearts go out to them more because they are helpless."
At the Web site www.networkforgood.org, donors can search for nonprofit groups by the type of charitable work they do, then make contributions online.
Donors for Katrina relief gave to more than 300 organizations through Network For Good, Andresen said.
On that list, the Humane Society (with $309000 in gifts) ranked behind Red Cross, Salvation Army and Catholic Charities USA, but ahead of Habitat for Humanity (with $264000 in gifts).
Animal advocacy groups said the level of giving to pet charities does not mean the donors value pets above people.
Rather, they said, this disaster showed the close relationship between humans and animals.
"People who gave felt the animals were related to people and wanted them to be OK," said Linda Lampkin, director for the Urban Institute's National Center for Charitable Statistics.
Pacelle, of the Humane Society, said having to choose between humans and pets is "a false choice.
A lot of people gave to both."
"There's a misconception that there's a finite amount of compassion," Pacelle said.
"People donated toward the human and animal victim."
Indeed, Andresen said Network For Good reported many people giving to more than one organization one that would help people and another that would help people's furry friends.
"Noah's Wish exists as much to help people as animals," added Crisp, explaining that the group has sheltered families, taken care of their pets free of charge and reunited pets with families.
"We're not taking away from anything by being here to take care of the animal needs.
If we weren't here, there would be a large percentage of animals that wouldn't have survived (the hurricane and its ensuing flood), and that would've been a huge loss for people."
Aside from donations, animal advocacy groups said the dramatic post disaster period opened up a window for them to educate the public about the importance of having a disaster plan for pets.
Said Pacelle, "People will never see animals in disaster in the same way."
After watching Hurricane Katrina's devastation from their Port Arthur, Texas, home, the Myers family made evacuation plans.
If ever they were forced to flee, the family would head to Marshall, in East Texas, where relatives would be waiting, Michael Myers said.
The men would go early one weekend and build a shelter for their dogs.
They ran out of time.
"We had a family meeting before Rita was a thunderstorm," Michael Myers said.
"We wanted to keep everyone together.
But Rita came so fast we weren't able to put that plan into motion."
The Myerses were luckier than many others.
They contacted kennel owner and animal lover Don Praeger in Arlington, Texas, who agreed to shelter their pets and those of other hurricane victims for free.
But many hurricane evacuees are still waiting to be reunited with their animals.
Thousands are being steered to Petfinder.com, a Web site updated daily with photographs of lost pets.
Nearly 8000 animals have been rescued from storm ravaged areas, said James Bias, president of the Texas Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
"We're still finding some animals alive," Bias said.
"Unfortunately, we're also finding many animals that have died."
The Louisiana staging area where many rescued animals have been kept since Katrina struck is being shut down, and owners have until Oct 15 to claim their animals from that site before they are put up for adoption, Bias said.
"That's not to say that you need to pick up the animal, but you need to be connected to the animal," Bias said.
To help return pets to their owners, the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and the Humane Society of the United States have established a fund to help pay transportation and other costs, said Karen Medicus, ASPCA project director based in Austin.
The two organizations will do "whatever it takes to get the animal back to their owners," Medicus said.
Animals have been shipped from Louisiana to different parts of the country and placed in animal shelters and foster homes until their owners can make provisions for them.
Listing lost pets on Petfinder beyond Dec 15 is unrealistic, some experts said.
"We've had a few really sad situations where people have had to release their pets to us because they have nothing left," said Angie Sprott, spokeswoman for the Humane Society of North Texas in Fort Worth.
Michael Myers and his 16 year old son are doing what they can to repay Praeger's kindness.
Each morning, they drive to Country Acres Kennel to help with cleaning and other odd jobs.
"I needed that help.
I couldn't afford to pay the money that they would normally charge," Myers said.
"I wanted to give him something back to show him how appreciative I was."
Myers said a neighbor told him his house in Port Arthur is in pretty decent shape.
He said he plans to take his family back sometime this week.
Those seeking animals lost in the storm are being routed to www.petfinder.com, an Internet clearing site containing pictures, descriptions and locations of lost pets.
Other resources: The Humane Society of the United States and the ASPCA will reimburse approved shelters the cost of transporting animals to their owners, up to $400.
For help grieving the death of a pet or for support after being separated from a pet, call the ASPCA's Pet Loss Hotline at (800) 946 4646, enter PIN 140 7211 and leave a telephone number.
A volunteer will return the page.
The national Humane Society, (800) 486 2631 or disaster@hsus.org.
