Libby entered the plea in the courtroom of U.S. District Judge Reggie B. Walton, an appointee of President Bush.
The grand jury indicted Libby, after a nearly two year investigation, on charges of perjury, obstruction of justice and making false statements.
The five count indictment charges that Libby lied to FBI agents and to the grand jury about how and when he came to learn classified information about a CIA operative, Valerie Plame.
If convicted on each count, Libby faces up to 30 years in prison and a $1.25 million fine.
Libby has acknowledged speaking to reporters about Plame, but has denied that he revealed that she was an undercover operative, which could be a violation of federal law.
The grand jury did not indict Karl Rove, President Bush's top political strategist, who had also become entangled in the investigation.
However, Patrick J. Fitzgerald, the special counsel in the case, said in announcing the indictment of Libby last week that the probe is "not over."
After his indictment last week, Libby issued a statement saying he expected to be "totally exonerated."
