Bush on Saturday sought to reassure conservatives, saying in his weekly radio address that Miers was a solid conservative who would not drift to the left if seated on the high court.
"I chose Harriet Miers for the court both because of her accomplishments, and because I know her character and her judicial philosophy.
Harriet Miers will be the type of judge I said I would nominate a good conservative judge," Bush said.
The chaos surrounding President Bush's Supreme Court nomination of Harriet Miers gets curiouser and curiouser.
Sen Patrick Leahy, D Vt., ranking member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, spoke for many Wednesday when he said, "We'd actually like to know what the heck is going on."
Thank goodness Leahy and committee Chairman Arlen Specter, R Pa., are working in a bipartisan way to protect the integrity of the Senate confirmation process and, ultimately, the integrity of the Supreme Court.
This nomination was in difficulty from the very start and for the right reason: questions about Miers' qualifications.
This is, after all, a lifetime appointment to the country's highest court.
Initially, the challenge to Miers came from conservatives, who wanted a nominee steeped in constitutional law and a firm believer in hewing closely to the language in the Constitution.
Miers has never been a judge, and by all accounts has little experience in constitutional law.
Bush sought to reassure at least the religious right by talking about Miers' strong evangelical religious beliefs, implying that she could be trusted to vote their way on culture war issues, including overturning Roe vs. Wade, the 1983 abortion ruling.
Indeed, recent news reports suggest the White House encouraged two judges in Texas who know Miers to hold a conference call with evangelical leaders in which the judges said flat out that Miers would vote to overturn Roe. That rightly raised both Republican and Democratic eyebrows.
But things just kept getting worse.
First, Specter, who is a very careful man, said Miers had endorsed the privacy concept in Griswold vs. Connecticut, a landmark decision on which the reasoning in Roe is based.
But Miers denied she'd told Specter that, leaving him dumbfounded and more than a little miffed.
Finally came Miers' responses to a questionnaire sent her by the Judiciary Committee.
According to Leahy, members of the committee on both sides of the aisle found the responses "inadequate," "insufficient" and "insulting."
Leahy and Specter asked her to do it over, with greater emphasis on precision.
As the New York Times remarked, this amounted to "a do over on a take home quiz."
Maybe it's Bush who needs a do over.
Leahy, Specter and their colleagues in both parties now seem loaded for bear as Miers' confirmation hearings approach, and that's a good thing.
If she comes out of those hearings looking as unqualified as she looks going in, the committee should reject her and ask Bush to send up another name.
