Embattled President George W. Bush, acknowledging a serious political defeat, announced Thursday that his choice to fill a US Supreme Court vacancy, Harriet Miers, had withdrawn her nomination.
"Today, I have reluctantly accepted Harriet Miers's decision to withdraw her nomination to the Supreme Court of the United States," he said.
"My responsibility to fill this vacancy remains.
I will do so in a timely manner."
The move came as Bush languished at his worst level ever in public opinion polls and faced the possible indictment of senior aides in connection to a criminal investigation into the unmasking of a CIA agent in 2003.
The court wields enormous influence over American life as the final arbiter of the US Constitution and ultimate court of appeal, and has ruled on issues like abortion, the death penalty and civil rights.
Justices are named for life but can step down.
Bush had anointed Miers a longtime aide who serves as White House counsel, his official government lawyer on October 3 to replace retiring Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor.
But the nomination immediately ran into trouble, with widespread accusations that the president had picked a crony, as well as a revolt from Bush's right wing base supporters, who saw her as insufficiently conservative.
There was also a brewing battle between the Bush administration and the US Senate, which must confirm justices, over access to her legal writings at the White House and over whether Miers would have to answer questions about specific issues likely to come before the court.
The White House refused to provide the documents and insisted that Miers, who has never been a judge, would not answer any precise queries about her beliefs on volatile issues like abortion.
Miers, 60, will stay on as White House counsel and is expected to help the president choose his next nominee for the nine seat US Supreme Court, according to Bush spokesman Scott McClellan.
McClellan told reporters that Miers had telephoned Bush at 8:30 pm Wednesday (0030 GMT Thursday) to let him know she was withdrawing, and formally offered him her resignation letter in the Oval Office 12 hours later.
In the letter, which was released by the White House, Miers said she was "concerned that the confirmation process presents a burden for the White House and our staff that is not in the best interest of the country.
"I have steadfastly maintained that the independence of the executive branch be preserved and its confidential documents and information not be released to further a confirmation process," she said.
Had she been confirmed, Miers would have joined Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg as the second woman on the court and the third in its history.
With Harriet Miers' sudden withdrawal, President Bush likely will choose a U.S. Supreme Court nominee who is conservative enough to mend the rift with his Republican base and qualified enough to fend off attacks from Democrats, experts said Thursday.
In other words, regardless of gender or race, Bush may need another John G. Roberts Jr. to replace retiring Justice Sandra Day O'Connor.
"John Roberts was the closest thing to perfect you are going to get," said Sen Lindsey Graham, R S.C., a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee that screens court nominees.
Bush promised to quickly name a replacement for Miers, the White House counsel who served as Bush's former personal attorney and president of the Texas Bar Association.
But with Bush's political troubles mounting, political and legal experts said the president must make a careful choice if he is to ease tensions and rally conservatives to his side.
Bush's public approval rating has sunk during the past few months with the continuation of violence in Iraq, high gasoline prices and the possibility that White House officials will be indicted today after a grand jury investigation of the leak of a CIA agent's identity.
Paul McGreal, a constitutional law professor at Houston's South Texas College of Law, said Roberts is the model to follow.
"With Harriet Miers, people were objecting on two fronts: She just didn't know enough about constitutional law, or there was not enough record to evaluate that, and conservatives didn't think she was one of them," he said.
"(Bush) needs to appoint someone with the public credentials of John Roberts a background and a record that people could look at and would have to say, 'Yeah, this person is qualified.'
But it also has to be someone who could meet the other credential for conservatives: 'Is he one of us?"'
Roberts, a conservative federal appeals court judge and a star appellate lawyer who had argued 39 cases before the high court and won 25 was confirmed last month to succeed the late Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
His paper trail appeared to be short because he had served on the bench only two years, but Roberts produced more than 70000 pages of written opinions, court briefs and other work demonstrating his familiarity with a wide variety of constitutional issues.
In meetings with senators and in four days of confirmation hearings, he wowed the Senate Judiciary Committee with his grasp of complex legal issues and his ability to cite from memory Supreme Court decisions and dissents.
Miers, on the other hand, is an accomplished corporate and government lawyer who has never been a judge and has rarely argued cases before appellate courts.
There are no opinions and very few legal briefs that could be used to assess her qualifications for the high court.
Miers said in a letter to the president that she was withdrawing to avoid burdening the White House with a struggle over access to documents on the advice she gave Bush as his government lawyer.
Senators indicated they would ask for the documents to help them gauge her qualifications, and Bush said this week he would refuse to provide them because they amounted to privileged information.
But beyond the issue of executive privilege, Miers faced attacks from conservative Republicans from the day of her nomination.
They accused Bush of cronyism and betrayal for picking his longtime friend over more solidly conservative candidates with stronger legal credentials.
Though no senator of either party had declared an intention to vote against her, Miers evidently concluded that her confirmation was unlikely or could be won only at severe personal cost.
"It's disappointing," said Sen John Cornyn, R Texas, "that this good person, that by any fair account is highly qualified, was not even given a chance for a hearing."
"This has been painful and difficult for everybody," said Wendy E. Long, counsel to the conservative Judicial Confirmation Network, which has worked to get Bush's past nominees confirmed but sat this one out.
"We initially tried to point out her virtues as a person, which we still stand by," Long said, "but the problem was there wasn't a whole lot to go on, or a whole lot in her record to fight with."
Long urged Bush to keep his campaign promise and select a nominee in the model of Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
"He campaigned twice for president and was very clear about what he was going to do, so it's no state secret," she said.
Asked who he would like to see nominated, Cornyn replied, "Anybody but me."
Bush and others have said they want wide representation on the Supreme Court a rationale for appointing a woman or a minority to replace O'Connor.
But most experts said it's more important for the president to pick an intellectually qualified nominee.
"My view is that there was zero pressure to appoint a woman or a minority when he appointed Harriet Miers," said Long.
"If the pressure was zero then, now it's utterly nonexistent."
Sen Dianne Feinstein, D Calif., the only woman on the Judiciary Committee, said it would be "a tremendous mistake" to appoint another member of the administration.
"It creates a perceived conflict," she said.
"Somebody has to have either the ability to entirely cut the umbilical cord or have no cord there in the first place."
Not two hours after the White House withdrew Harriet Miers's Supreme Court nomination Thursday morning, Trent Lott, R Miss., walked out of the Senate chamber with a spring in his step.
"I raised red flags the first day," the senator from I told you so said.
Asked if there was a sense of relief in the Republican caucus, Lott paused, smiled and, in his barbershop quartet bass, sang out to disbelieving reporters: "Happy Days Are Here Again!"
Senators came to bury Miers Thursday, not to praise her.
Republicans blamed the withdrawal on demands for White House documents.
Democrats blamed right wing ideologues.
But few seemed distraught that the nation would be spared the equivalent of a televised bar exam before the Senate Judiciary Committee next month.
As is customary, Sen Charles Schumer, D N.Y., was first to the microphones.
The first bulletins on Miers crossed the wires at 8:54 a.m.
At 9:32 a.m. Schumer announced a news conference for 10 a.m. "Harriet Miers is a fine and capable person, but this was clearly the wrong position for her," he announced.
Sen George Allen, R Va., was not far behind, at 10:22.
"I appreciate Harriet Miers's decision to withdraw," the conservative said.
The ostensible reason for the withdrawal what Miers called "protection of the prerogatives of the Executive Branch" from senators' demands for White House documents fell apart instantly.
"It wasn't only the documents," Miers's White House assigned shepherd, former senator Dan Coats, R Ind., told reporters outside the Senate chamber.
"Obviously you hope for unanimous support from your base when the president nominates someone, and that was lacking, as you know.
There were legitimate questions being asked about her background because she didn't have a paper trail."
Then there was the prospect of a week of grilling by the Judiciary Committee.
"She was," Coats added, "doing very well in her trial preparations."
Trial?
"Freudian slip," the shepherd explained.
It's understandable that Coats would be off message: Miers told Bush last night that she was dropping out, but nobody bothered to tell Coats.
"I got up this morning looking forward to more consultations," he said.
"When I arrived at the White House early, we went into a private office, and we had a discussion."
Reporters, expecting a routine day on the Hill, rushed to the Senate chamber in the morning for an otherwise unremarkable vote on a labor spending bill.
A trio of Judiciary Committee Republicans Jeff Sessions of Alabama, Mike DeWine of Ohio and John Cornyn of Texas gave impromptu news conferences.
Sessions was not distraught.
"I was concerned about the, uh, concern," he said.
"Probably she was worried about (it), too."
Cornyn, Miers's friend and most ardent Senate supporter, insinuated that the Democrats were to blame.
"I would just say it's part of unnecessary contentiousness and partisanship," he argued.
When a questioner pointed out that the objections came primarily from Republicans, Cornyn turned angrily.
"There is no Republican senator who opposed the nominee," he said.
"Your statement was wrong!"
The growls subsided when Cornyn, an hour later, was asked at another news conference about the possibility that he could be nominated to the high court.
"Well, you know, if the president calls me, obviously I'll answer the phone or go see him, if he invites me to come to the White House," he said.
Democrats, though they never committed to supporting Miers, lined up to blame the "right wing" (John Kerry), "the far right wing" (Byron Dorgan), "extreme right wing" (Dick Durbin), "extreme partisan pressure" (Mary Landrieu) and "extremists" (Ted Kennedy).
The Democrats got some help making this point from Judiciary Chairman Arlen Specter, R Pa., who made a terse statement on the Senate floor.
Specter the man who suggested the nominee needed a "crash course in constitutional law" lamented the "one sided debate" and the "heavy decibel level against her."
Rebutting the White House line, Specter argued that "the Judiciary Committee carefully did not intrude on the president's executive privilege."
His three minute statement over, Specter left the chamber through a back door, evading the scrum of reporters waiting to ambush him.
Lott, the Senate Republican leader Bush helped to dethrone, was happy to talk.
And he didn't have anything nice to say.
On Bush's nominees: "I'm not going to just roll over and take everything he sends up here."
On Bush's consultations: "I don't think he got enough advice from the right people."
On Attorney General Alberto Gonzales for the court: "Forget that!"
Asked why Bush chose Miers, Lott replied: "There is Federalist Paper number 76.
I invite your attention to it: Be careful about home state, personal friends, cronyism."
Lott had more to say.
He branded Bush's aides "all young and inexperienced" and said senators had nobody to call at the White House.
"Karl Rove can't do it all by himself," Lott said.
Then a mischievous grin crossed the senator's face, and, alluding to the CIA leak case, he added: "And he may not be there."
Theatrically, Lott brushed his hands as if wiping off dust.
US President George W. Bush faces a delicate balancing act in nominating a new Supreme Court justice who will appeal to the religious right but not spark fierce Democratic opposition, following Harriet Miers's abrupt withdrawal.
Bush has said he will move "quickly" to select another candidate for America's highest court, after Miers withdrew from the process Thursday amid a firestorm of opposition from right wing lawmakers and religious groups.
Rattled by a CIA leak scandal that has targeted a top White House aide, and taking fire on Iraq and his administration's response to the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina, Bush must confound suggestions of weakness and perceptions that his power is already ebbing, according to political analysts.
A Bush administration official, who requested anonymity, said the White House has gone back to reviewing a potential list of nominees that it had mulled before the president announced Miers as his pick on October 3.
Her nomination had run into trouble on Capitol Hill, where lawmakers suggested she lacked the votes necessary for confirmation to the United States' highest court.
Even lawmakers in Bush's own Republican Party had questioned Miers's conservative credentials and grasp of constitutional law.
Miers, Bush's White House counsel and a former Texas lawyer, said in a letter to Bush that she had withdrawn her nomination in order to protect the independence of the executive branch.
"I have steadfastly maintained that the independence of the executive branch be preserved and its confidential documents and information not be released to further a confirmation process," she said in the letter released to the media.
Supreme Court justices must be approved by the Senate, after being nominated by a US president, before they can take a seat on the court.
A vacancy opened up on the court after Justice Sandra Day O'Connor announced her retirement from the nine member bench.
O'Connor has said she will stay on until a new justice has been approved to take her post.
Conservatives said Bush will now have to come up with a "winnable conservative nominee" for the court.
"The flow of blood has been stanched," said David Keene, chairman of the American Conservative Union.
"If he (Bush) comes up with a winnable conservative nominee, even if that person faces a fight in Congress, he will have drawn his people back to him," Keene noted.
Other conservatives said Miers's failed nomination had shown how out of touch the Republican president was with some of his key political supporters.
"What has come out of this episode is how really out of touch Mr Bush is with the intellectual foundations of the movement that he purports to represent," said Roger Pilon, director of the Center for Constitutional Studies at the libertarian Cato Institute.
Some Supreme Court watchers, meanwhile, said Bush might have even less of a choice this time around as he vies to appoint a successful candidate to the court.
"The president appears to have less flexibility about what he does next, and the moderate Republican senators probably gain some power to determine the fate of a new nominee.
The Democrats, on the other hand, may not realize much advantage, if any," the Scotusblog.com website said in a posting.
Republican Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi played down Miers's failed nomination.
"Let's move on," he urged, adding: "In a month, who will remember the name Harriet Miers?"
The withdrawal of Harriet E. Miers from Supreme Court consideration was greeted Thursday with a blend of regret, relief and a general feeling that she had not been treated very well.
"This is a sad episode," said Sen Arlen Specter, the Pennsylvania Republican who heads the Senate Judiciary Committee and who not long ago said Miers needed "a crash course in constitutional law."
"Whether or not she would have been confirmed is an open question," Specter said, voicing regret that Miers did not last long enough for a committee hearing, where "she would have had a major voice in determining her own future."
Democrats on the committee, while stopping far short of endorsing her, nonetheless expressed sympathy for the erstwhile nominee.
"The right wing effectively killed this nomination," Sen Dianne Feinstein of California said on CNN.
Feinstein said Miers "may not be the best thing since sliced bread" as far as her qualifications, but "I don't think she deserved the treatment she got."
Sen Charles E. Schumer of New York, another Judiciary Committee member, said, "Harriet Miers is a fine and capable person, but this was clearly the wrong position for her.
Her gracious withdrawal saves Harriet Miers and the nation from a difficult and agonizing process and decision."
Some senators said Miers had been the victim of bad handling by a White House that capitulated to people in the far right wing of the Republican Party who doubted the depth of her conservative beliefs.
Other senators, like Schumer, said the nomination had been bungled from the start, and that President Bush should never have chosen a person who was not qualified for the Supreme Court, whatever her other legal credentials and personal attributes.
"This nominee deserved better," said Sen Edward M. Kennedy, D Mass., a committee member.
While by no means indicating he would have voted for her, Kennedy said he respected Miers: "She has been a woman of achievement in her career."
The other Democrat from Massachusetts, Sen John Kerry, said President Bush had surrendered to "right wing interest groups" and let them determine the fate of Miers.
"This nomination was mishandled from the beginning," said Kerry, who is not on the Judiciary Committee.
"The president nominated someone whose qualifications he alone knew, then refused to disclose the only documents that would give the Senate even a hint of his nominee's judicial philosophy."
Sen George Voinovich, R Ohio, said, "Various groups, particularly on the Republican side, didn't give her the opportunity to share why she's qualified."
And Judge Robert H. Bork, who knows the pain of being nominated for the Supreme Court and never getting there, said, "We all have to have some sympathy for her."
Bork, who was rejected by the Senate in 1987, said in a CNN interview that Miers had been nominated for a position for which she was not really qualified.
"I think it was appropriate for her to withdraw," he said.
Fairly or not, the nomination of Miers was accompanied by charges of cronyism.
The White House spokesman, Scott McClellan, was asked Thursday whether it was a safe bet that the president's next choice would not be a White House employee.
"He will let you know who the next nominee is in due course," McClellan replied.
Saddened and surprised, friends and associates of Harrier Miers' in Texas blamed harsh attacks by the Christian conservatives, along with a bungled White House strategy to sell with her nomination, with sinking the Dallas attorney's nomination to the nation's highest court.
"I feel very proud of Harriet and at the same time sorry for her," said Darrell Jordan, a Dallas attorney.
"She is the most decent and honorable person in the world, and to have it end like this is very disappointing."
In Washington last week to stump for Miers with the Senate Judiciary Committee, Jordan said the White House committed several "gaffes," including touting Miers' religious background to appease Christian conservatives who criticized Bush's nomination.
"I wondered from the beginning why they were taking that approach.
It was a risky strategy," Jordan said.
Molly Steele, a former Dallas Bar Association president who worked with Miers, said she was sorry that her friend would not be allowed to bring her considerable legal skills as a trial attorney to the court.
"I think she would have been imminently fair and reasonable.
She would have been a centralist vote like (Supreme Court Justice) Sandra Day O'Connor," Steele said.
"It is obvious the next appointee could be a right wing ideologue like the base of the Republican Party wants."
At Locke Liddell & Sapp, the massive Dallas law firm where Miers worked before moving to Washington in 2001, the front lobby was virtually empty, the mood seemed somber.
"We're disappointed that our friend and colleague ,has withdrawn her nomination to be a justice on the Supreme Court of the United States, and that she never received a fair hearing," said a spokeswoman for the firm, Julie Gilbert, reading from a prepared statement.
"Harriet Miers has led a distinguished career, has an impeccable reputation, was extremely qualified and would have served the American people well," Gilbert said from the law firm's offices in Houston.
"We are proud of all Harriet Miers did for this law firm ,Professionally and personally, she remains a role model for us all," she said.
Cathie Adams of Dallas, president of the conservative group Texas Eagle Forum, credited Miers for doing "the right thing" by withdrawing.
"I think that she is not a conservative, ideologically," Adams said, "and I am disappointed in her embracing of too many facets of the feminist agenda, gender quotas in particular."
Adams said federal appeals court Judges Janice Rogers Brown and Edith Hollan Jones both have "conservative paper trails" suitable for nomination to the Supreme Court.
But, Adams said she would also support "another qualified gentleman because I don't think we have to have a gender quota."
Bush nominated Miers to the court a little more than three weeks ago, immediately angering members of the Christian right who said Bush had promised them a conservative court nominee in the mold of Supreme Court justices Clarence Thomas or Antonin Scalia.
Republicans and Democrats complained about her lack of judicial experience, and members of the Judiciary Committee sharply criticized Miers for not completely answering a questionnaire about her work at the White House.
The administration made available about 9000 pages of documents from Miers' tenure on the Dallas City Council and the Texas Lottery Commission, and Miers friends responded by pointing to her record as a "trailblazer."
Miers was the first woman hired by Lock Purnell Boren Laney & Neely, a blue chip Dallas law firm with roots back to the late 1800s.
She later became that firms managing partner, overseeing a team of more than 400 lawyers.
She also was the first woman president of the Dallas Bar Association in 1983, and the first woman president of the State Bar of Texas in 1992 93.
During her work with those groups and the American Bar Association, Miers earned high marks for reaching out to women and minorities and for working to improve legal services to the poor.
"Everybody who ever worked with her knew she was fair," Jordan said.
An outstanding lawyer and person, Miers would have been a fine Supreme Court justice, said Derek Davis, director of the J.M. Dawson Institute of Church State Studies at Baylor University.
Davis is an attorney who used to practice a few floors away from Miers.
He blamed "ultra conservatives" with destroying Miers' nomination because they insisted on having a justice that would change social policy in two areas: abortion and the trend of accepting homosexuality.
"They feel like they put George Bush into office and this was part of his promise to revamp the court.
But he's not revamping it in the way they want," Davis said.
Steele was on her way to breakfast with a friend Thursday when she heard that Miers had dropped out.
She said she had not yet talked to her friend.
"But I'm going to call and leave her a message and say we still love her and leave it at that," Steele said.
