Zhao Tiechui, deputy director of China's mine safety agency, appealed to the public and mine employees to report safety violations and accidents that mine managers try to cover up.
Regulators received 16 tips this year about attempts to cover up accidents that killed a total of 41 people, Zhao said.
The government has created a fund to pay whistleblowers up to 10000 yuan (US$1200, euro1000) for tips, Zhao said.
Such a reward is a huge sum in a country where the average worker makes about US$1000 a year, and many families get by on far less.
