One leading candidate has been debilitated by what he said was an attempt to poison him.
A thrown egg did more than smear the coat of another.
A mysteriously rescheduled military parade has fueled rumors of plans for a state of emergency.
Attack ads have explored the depths of what is known here as "black propaganda."
"It's like 'The Matrix,"' said Andrei Gurin, who was not the only voter here to describe Ukraine's presidential campaign as something close to cinematic.
"Nothing to trust, nothing to believe."
President Leonid D. Kuchma's decision not to seek a third five year term after maneuvering to change the constitution to allow it has opened a fierce and increasingly nasty presidential campaign.
The leading candidates are offering starkly different visions, especially in foreign relations.
With election day less than a month away, on Oct 31, polls suggest a tight race between the most prominent of two dozen candidates: Viktor A. Yushchenko, a former prime minister and central banker and now the leader of the anti Kuchma opposition, and Viktor F. Yanukovich, the current prime minister, who promises to carry out much of Kuchma's legacy.
Neither front runner is expected to win an outright majority.
A runoff is scheduled for Nov 21.
The race is one of the most competitive in a former Soviet state, and its outcome could significantly alter the course of this country with 47 million people at an important crossroads of Europe.
Yushchenko, who appears to hold a slight lead in the polls, has long been pro Western and encouraging free market reforms.
He has promised to steer Ukraine toward a more open and democratic society, ending what he calls the cronyism and corruption of Kuchma's 10 years in power.
Yushchenko has vowed to improve economic and political relations with the European Union and NATO, while withdrawing Ukraine's 1600 troops from Iraq.
Like many here, he argues that Kuchma dispatched the force largely to improve tattered ties with the Bush administration.
Yanukovich's economic and social pledges echo his opponent's, but in his view Ukraine's future depends on closer relations with Russia, the country's largest trading partner.
He remains more reserved about Europe and the United States, but has said he would not withdraw Ukrainian troops from Iraq until democratic elections are held there.
"Whoever is the victor, the direction will be clear," said Yuliya V. Tymoshenko, a supporter of Yushchenko's who has criticized Kuchma's alternating efforts to improve relations with the West and then with Russia.
"At least a choice will be made.
We are tired of the president and his team pulling the compass of foreign policy everywhere."
Each candidate's campaign has used foreign policy to attack the other.
Posters found in a warehouse and confiscated by Yushchenko's supporters last week depicted the candidate as a tool of the United States.
One showed President Bush riding Ukraine like a horse under Yushchenko's campaign logo.
Yushchenko's supporters in turn deride Yanukovich, accusing him of seeking to appease Russia.
Yanukovich gave his opponents ammunition with a trip to Moscow that included a meeting on Saturday with President Vladimir V. Putin, who all but endorsed his candidacy.
Whether the candidates' competing visions decide the vote remains very much an open question, largely because they have been overshadowed by the strange twists of the campaign.
Yushchenko has spent much of the last month in a hospital in Austria, after falling ill on Sept 6 from what he and his supporters called an attempt to poison him.
After returning to Kiev to resume campaigning on Sept 18, he accused Kuchma's government of an assassination attempt.
"You will not poison us," Yushchenko said to the government at a large rally of supporters in Kiev that day.
"You do not have enough bullets and trucks to break us."
On Sept 30, however, Yushchenko returned to Austria for treatment of his ailments, including paralysis in the left side of his face.
"The illness is much worse than we thought," said Oleksandr O. Zinchenko, a member of the national legislature and chairman of Yushchenko's campaign, speaking in an interview.
Yushchenko only returned to Ukraine on Sunday night, appearing wan and visibly weakened, in Lviv, the western city where his support is deepest, according to televised reports.
On Monday, he returned to the campaign trail in Kiev.
"I am alive, I am OK, and I am back," Yushchenko told a large crowd of supporters.
In his absence, surrogates have stumped on Yushchenko's behalf, even as the legislature, controlled by a coalition opposed to Kuchma, authorized an investigation into his accusations.
The hospital in Vienna, Rudolfinerhaus, first issued a statement discounting the possibility of poisoning, only to retract it, saying it was impossible to rule it out.
Then the chairman of the legislature's investigation committee, Volodimir Sivkovich, stunned Yushchenko's supporters by declaring before the legislature that there was no evidence to suggest an assassination attempt, although he did not rule out that Yushchenko might have been poisoned.
He said in an interview that "neither Yushchenko nor his headquarters had any legal right to say that someone made an attempt on his life."
"In our country there are a lot of lies, more than any other country in the world," Sivkovich said.
Yanukovich's supporters have leveled their own accusations of an attempted assassination.
On Sept 24, Yanukovich collapsed while campaigning in Ivano Frankivsk.
His aides said at the time that he was struck in the head by a blunt object and blamed supporters of Yushchenko.
A video, however, clearly shows that an egg struck him in the chest as he stepped off his campaign bus.
After two or three seconds, he clutched his chest and collapsed into the arms of his aides, who whisked him to a hospital, although he appeared to have been unhurt.
The attack, like all of Yanukovich's campaign events, received prominent attention on the country's television networks, all but one of which is owned or controlled by the government.
That has prompted accusations that the government is using all its resources to favor Yanukovich.
A parade to celebrate the 60th anniversary of Kiev's liberation from Nazi Germany on Nov 6, 1944, has been moved forward to Oct 28, three days before the election.
Opponents see that as an election ploy or, worse, evidence for a military crackdown.
Sergei L. Vasiliyev, chief spokesman for Kuchma's administration, insisted that the election would be free and fair.
"We do not have an experience with any other kind," he said, referring to the country's post Soviet presidential elections.
He said Yanukovich's dominance in news reports reflected his official duties as prime minister.
The egg attack appears to have engendered little sympathy, prompting ridicule and at least one pointed joke.
A grandmother goes to the market, the joke goes, and when finished with her shopping sees an official portrait of Yanukovich.
"Oy," she says, "I forgot to buy eggs."
Yanukovich's opponents have made accusations of serious violations of election laws, though, as have Ukrainian and international election observers.
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe reported recently that campaign events have been disrupted, while students and public employees have been pressured to support Yanukovich's candidacy.
Oleksandr O. Moroz, a member of the legislature and the perennial Socialist Party candidate for president, accused the government of "seriously preparing for falsifying the results" on Yanukovich's behalf.
He said Kuchma might even cancel the election outright, if Yanukovich risked losing.
Vasiliyev, the presidential spokesman, called that "complete nonsense."
Moroz, who trails distantly in the polls, said the circumstances surrounding the campaign has obscured the country's serious problems.
They include, he said in an interview in his office, social inequities, an economy controlled by a handful of tycoons close to the government, corruption and what he called "state criminality" under Kuchma.
He called the election an important choice for Ukraine.
"People," he said, "are tired of scandals."
